# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: t-cell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The **human immunodeficiency virus** (HIV) is a retrovirus that attacks the immune system.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Without treatment, it can lead to a spectrum of conditions including **acquired immunodeficiency syndrome** (AIDS).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It can be managed with treatment and become a manageable chronic health condition.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] While there is no cure or vaccine for HIV, antiretroviral treatment can slow the course of the disease, and, if used before significant disease progression, can extend the life expectancy of someone living with HIV to a nearly standard level.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] An HIV-positive person on treatment can expect to live a normal life, and die with the virus, not of it.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Effective treatment for HIV-positive people (people living with HIV) involves a life-long regimen of medicine to suppress the virus, making the viral load undetectable.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Early testing can show if treatment is needed to stop progression and to prevent infecting others.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Treatment is recommended as soon as the diagnosis is made.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] An HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Campaigns by UNAIDS and other organizations around the world have communicated this as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Without treatment the infection can interfere with the immune system, and eventually progress to AIDS, sometimes taking many years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Following initial infection an individual may not notice any symptoms, or may experience a brief period of influenza-like illness.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] During this period the person may not know that they are HIV-positive, yet they will be able to pass on the virus.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Typically, this period is followed by a prolonged incubation period with no symptoms.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Eventually the HIV infection increases the risk of developing other infections such as tuberculosis, as well as other opportunistic infections, and tumors which are rare in people who have normal immune function.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The late stage is often also associated with unintended weight loss.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Without treatment, the life expectancy of an individual with HIV is around 11 years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is spread primarily by unprotected sex (including anal, oral and vaginal sex), contaminated hypodermic needles or blood transfusions, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Some bodily fluids, such as saliva, sweat, and tears, do not transmit the virus.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Oral sex has little risk of transmitting the virus.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Ways to avoid catching HIV and preventing the spread include safe sex, treatment to prevent infection ("PrEP"), treatment to stop infection in someone who has been recently exposed ("PEP"), treating those who are infected, and needle exchange programs.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Disease in a baby can often be prevented by giving both the mother and child antiretroviral medication.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Recognized worldwide in the early 1980s, HIV/AIDS has had a large impact on society, both as an illness and as a source of discrimination.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The disease also has large economic impacts.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There are many misconceptions about HIV/AIDS, such as the belief that it can be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The disease has become subject to many controversies involving religion, including the Catholic Church's position not to support condom use as prevention.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It has attracted international medical and political attention as well as large-scale funding since it was identified in the 1980s.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV made the jump from other primates to humans in west-central Africa in the early-to-mid-20th century.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 1981 and its cause—HIV infection—was identified in the early part of the decade.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Between the first time AIDS was readily identified through 2024, the disease is estimated to have caused at least 42.3 million deaths worldwide.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In 2025, 1.2 million people acquired HIV and an estimated 40.9 million people worldwide were living with HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a pandemic—a disease outbreak which is present over a large area and is actively spreading.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The United States' National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the Gates Foundation have pledged $200 million focused on developing a global cure for AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There are three main stages of HIV infection: acute infection, clinical latency, and AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The initial period following infection with HIV is called acute HIV, primary HIV or acute retroviral syndrome.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Many individuals develop an influenza-like illness, mononucleosis or glandular fever 2–4 weeks after exposure while others have no significant symptoms.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Symptoms occur in 40–90% of cases and most commonly include fever, large tender lymph nodes, throat inflammation, a rash, headache, tiredness, and/or sores of the mouth and genitals.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The rash, which occurs in 20–50% of cases, presents itself on the trunk and is maculopapular, classically.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Some people also develop opportunistic infections at this stage.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Gastrointestinal symptoms, such as vomiting or diarrhea may occur.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Neurological symptoms of peripheral neuropathy or Guillain–Barré syndrome also occur.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The duration of the symptoms varies, but is usually one or two weeks.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] These symptoms are not often recognized as signs of HIV infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Family doctors or hospitals can misdiagnose cases as one of the many common infectious diseases with similar symptoms.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Someone with an unexplained fever who may have been recently exposed to HIV should consider testing to find out if they have been infected.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The initial symptoms are followed by a stage called clinical latency, asymptomatic HIV, or chronic HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Without treatment, this second stage of the natural history of HIV infection can last from about three years to over 20 years (on average, about eight years).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] While typically there are few or no symptoms at first, near the end of this stage many people experience fever, weight loss, gastrointestinal problems and muscle pains.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Between 50% and 70% of people also develop persistent generalized lymphadenopathy, characterized by unexplained, non-painful enlargement of more than one group of lymph nodes (other than in the groin) for over three to six months.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Although most HIV-1 infected individuals have a detectable viral load and in the absence of treatment will eventually progress to AIDS, a small proportion (about 5%) retain high levels of CD4+ T cells (T helper cells) without antiretroviral therapy for more than five years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] These individuals are classified as "HIV controllers" or long-term nonprogressors (LTNP).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Another group consists of those who maintain a low or undetectable viral load without anti-retroviral treatment, known as "elite controllers" or "elite suppressors".
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] They represent approximately 1 in 300 infected persons.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) is defined as an HIV infection with either a CD4+ T cell count below 200 cells per microlitre (μL) of blood or the occurrence of specific diseases associated with HIV infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the absence of specific treatment, around half of people infected with HIV develop AIDS within ten years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The most common initial conditions that alert to the presence of AIDS are pneumocystis pneumonia (40%), cachexia in the form of HIV wasting syndrome (20%), and esophageal candidiasis.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Other common signs include recurrent respiratory tract infections.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Opportunistic infections may be caused by bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites that are normally controlled by the immune system.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Which infections occur depends partly on what organisms are common in the person's environment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] These infections may affect nearly every organ system.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] People with AIDS have an increased risk of developing various viral-induced cancers, including Kaposi's sarcoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Kaposi's sarcoma is the most common cancer, occurring in 10% to 20% of people with HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The second-most common cancer is lymphoma, which is the cause of death of nearly 16% of people with AIDS and is the initial sign of AIDS in 3% to 4%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Both these cancers are associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Cervical cancer occurs more frequently in those with AIDS because of its association with human papillomavirus (HPV).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Conjunctival cancer (of the layer that lines the inner part of eyelids and the white part of the eye) is also more common in those with HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Additionally, people with AIDS frequently have systemic symptoms such as prolonged fevers, sweats (particularly at night), swollen lymph nodes, chills, weakness, and unintended weight loss.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Diarrhea is another common symptom, present in about 90% of people with AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] They can also be affected by diverse psychiatric and neurological symptoms independent of opportunistic infections and cancers.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is spread by three main routes: sexual contact, significant exposure to infected body fluids or tissues, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding (known as vertical transmission).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There is no risk of acquiring HIV if exposed to feces, nasal secretions, saliva, sputum, sweat, tears, urine, or vomit unless these are contaminated with blood.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is also possible to be co-infected by more than one strain of HIV—a condition known as HIV superinfection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The most frequent mode of transmission of HIV is through sexual contact with an infected person.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] However, an HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually, known as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The existence of functionally noncontagious HIV-positive people on antiretroviral therapy was controversially publicized in the 2008 Swiss Statement, and has since become accepted as medically sound.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Globally, the most common mode of HIV transmission is via sexual contacts between people of the opposite sex; however, the pattern of transmission varies among countries.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] As of 2017, most HIV transmission in the United States occurred among men who had sex with men (82% of new HIV diagnoses among males aged 13 and older and 70% of total new diagnoses).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the US, gay and bisexual men aged 13 to 24 accounted for an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group and 27% of new diagnoses among all gay and bisexual men.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] With regard to unprotected heterosexual contacts, estimates of the risk of HIV transmission per sexual act appear to be four to ten times higher in low-income countries than in high-income countries.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The risk of transmission from anal intercourse is especially high, estimated as 1.4–1.7% per act in both heterosexual and homosexual contacts.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] While the risk of transmission from oral sex is relatively low, it is still present.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The risk from receiving oral sex has been described as "nearly nil"; however, a few cases have been reported.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The per-act risk is estimated at 0–0.04% for receptive oral intercourse.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In settings involving prostitution in low-income countries, risk of female-to-male transmission has been estimated as 2.4% per act, and of male-to-female transmission as 0.05% per act.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Risk of transmission increases in the presence of many sexually transmitted infections and genital ulcers.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Genital ulcers increase the risk approximately fivefold.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Other sexually transmitted infections, such as gonorrhea, chlamydia, trichomoniasis, and bacterial vaginosis, are associated with somewhat smaller increases in risk of transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The viral load of an infected person is an important risk factor in both sexual and mother-to-child transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] During the first 2.5 months of an HIV infection, a person's infectiousness is twelve times higher due to the high viral load associated with acute HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If the person is in the late stages of infection, rates of transmission are approximately eightfold greater.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Commercial sex workers (including those in pornography) have an increased likelihood of contracting HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Rough sex can be a factor associated with an increased risk of transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Sexual assault is also believed to carry an increased risk of HIV transmission, as condoms are rarely worn, physical trauma to the vagina or rectum is likely, and there may be a greater risk of concurrent sexually transmitted infections.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The second-most frequent mode of HIV transmission is via blood and blood products.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Blood-borne transmission can be through needle-sharing during intravenous drug use, needle-stick injury, transfusion of contaminated blood or blood product, or medical injections with unsterilized equipment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The risk from sharing a needle during drug injection is between 0.63% and 2.4% per act, with an average of 0.8%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The risk of acquiring HIV from a needle stick from an HIV-infected person is estimated as 0.3% (about 1 in 333) per act and the risk following mucous membrane exposure to infected blood as 0.09% (about 1 in 1000) per act.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This risk may, however, be up to 5% if the introduced blood was from a person with a high viral load and the cut was deep.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the United States, intravenous drug users made up 12% of all new cases of HIV in 2009, and in some areas more than 80% of people who inject drugs are predicted to be HIV-positive.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is transmitted in about 90% of blood transfusions using infected blood.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In low-income countries, only half of transfusions may be appropriately screened (as of 2008), and it is estimated that up to 15% of HIV infections in these areas come from transfusion of infected blood and blood products, representing between 5% and 10% of global infections.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is possible to acquire HIV from organ and tissue transplantation, although this is rare because of screening.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Unsafe medical injections play a role in HIV spread in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In 2007, between 12% and 17% of infections in this region were attributed to medical syringe use.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The World Health Organization estimates the risk of transmission as a result of a medical injection in Africa at 1.2%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Risks are also associated with invasive procedures, assisted delivery, and dental care in this area of the world.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] People giving or receiving tattoos, piercings, and scarification are theoretically at risk of infection but no confirmed cases have been documented.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is not possible for mosquitoes or other insects to transmit HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV can be transmitted from mother to child during pregnancy, during delivery, or through breast milk, resulting in the baby also contracting HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] As of 2008, vertical transmission accounted for about 90% of cases of HIV in children.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the absence of treatment, the risk of transmission before or during birth is around 20%, and in those who also breastfeed 35%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Treatment decreases this risk to less than 5%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Antiretrovirals when taken by either the mother or the baby decrease the risk of transmission in those who do breastfeed.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If blood contaminates food during pre-chewing it may pose a risk of transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If a woman is untreated, two years of breastfeeding results in an HIV/AIDS risk in her baby of about 17%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Due to the increased risk of death without breastfeeding in many areas in the developing world, the World Health Organization recommends either exclusive breastfeeding or the provision of safe formula.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] All women known to be HIV-positive should be taking lifelong antiretroviral therapy.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is the cause of the spectrum of disease known as HIV/AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is a retrovirus that primarily infects components of the human immune system such as CD4+ T cells, macrophages and dendritic cells.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It directly and indirectly destroys CD4+ T cells.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is a member of the genus *Lentivirus*, part of the family *Retroviridae*.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Lentiviruses share many morphological and biological characteristics.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Many species of mammals are infected by lentiviruses, which are characteristically responsible for long-duration illnesses with a long incubation period.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Lentiviruses are transmitted as single-stranded, positive-sense, enveloped RNA viruses.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Upon entry into the target cell, the viral RNA genome is converted (reverse transcribed) into double-stranded DNA by a virally encoded reverse transcriptase that is transported along with the viral genome in the virus particle.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The resulting viral DNA is then imported into the cell nucleus and integrated into the cellular DNA by a virally encoded integrase and host co-factors.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Once integrated, the virus may become latent, allowing the virus and its host cell to avoid detection by the immune system.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Alternatively, the virus may be transcribed, producing new RNA genomes and viral proteins that are packaged and released from the cell as new virus particles that begin the replication cycle anew.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is now known to spread between CD4+ T cells by two parallel routes: cell-free spread and cell-to-cell spread, i.e. it employs hybrid spreading mechanisms.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the cell-free spread, virus particles bud from an infected T cell, enter the blood/extracellular fluid and then infect another T cell following a chance encounter.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV can also disseminate by direct transmission from one cell to another by a process of cell-to-cell spread.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The hybrid spreading mechanisms of HIV contribute to the virus' ongoing replication against antiretroviral therapies.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Two types of HIV have been characterized: HIV-1 and HIV-2.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV-1 is the virus that was originally discovered (and initially referred to also as LAV or HTLV-III).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is more virulent, more infective, and is the cause of the majority of HIV infections globally.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The lower infectivity of HIV-2 as compared with HIV-1 implies that fewer people exposed to HIV-2 will be infected per exposure.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Because of its relatively poor capacity for transmission, HIV-2 is largely confined to West Africa.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] After the virus enters the body, there is a period of rapid viral replication, leading to an abundance of virus in the peripheral blood.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] During primary infection, the level of HIV may reach several million virus particles per milliliter of blood.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This response is accompanied by a marked drop in the number of circulating CD4+ T cells.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The acute viremia is almost invariably associated with activation of CD8+ T cells, which kill HIV-infected cells, and subsequently with antibody production, or seroconversion.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The CD8+ T cell response is thought to be important in controlling virus levels, which peak and then decline, as the CD4+ T cell counts recover.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] A good CD8+ T cell response has been linked to slower disease progression and a better prognosis, though it does not eliminate the virus.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Ultimately, HIV causes AIDS by depleting CD4+ T cells.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This weakens the immune system and allows opportunistic infections.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] T cells are essential to the immune response and without them, the body cannot fight infections or kill cancerous cells.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The mechanism of CD4+ T cell depletion differs in the acute and chronic phases.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] During the acute phase, HIV-induced cell lysis and killing of infected cells by CD8+ T cells accounts for CD4+ T cell depletion, although apoptosis may also be a factor.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] During the chronic phase, the consequences of generalized immune activation coupled with the gradual loss of the ability of the immune system to generate new T cells appear to account for the slow decline in CD4+ T cell numbers.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Although the symptoms of immune deficiency characteristic of AIDS do not appear for years after a person is infected, the bulk of CD4+ T cell loss occurs during the first weeks of infection, especially in the intestinal mucosa, which harbors the majority of the lymphocytes found in the body.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The reason for the preferential loss of mucosal CD4+ T cells is that the majority of mucosal CD4+ T cells express the CCR5 protein which HIV uses as a co-receptor to gain access to the cells, whereas only a small fraction of CD4+ T cells in the bloodstream do so.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] A specific genetic change that alters the CCR5 protein when present in both chromosomes very effectively prevents HIV-1 infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV seeks out and destroys CCR5 expressing CD4+ T cells during acute infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] A vigorous immune response eventually controls the infection and initiates the clinically latent phase.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] CD4+ T cells in mucosal tissues remain particularly affected.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Continuous HIV replication causes a state of generalized immune activation persisting throughout the chronic phase.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Immune activation, which is reflected by the increased activation state of immune cells and release of pro-inflammatory cytokines, results from the activity of several HIV gene products and the immune response to ongoing HIV replication.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is also linked to the breakdown of the immune surveillance system of the gastrointestinal mucosal barrier caused by the depletion of mucosal CD4+ T cells during the acute phase of disease.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV/AIDS related eye diseases are common among people living with this disease worldwide.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Among these diseases, HIV retinopathy is the most common condition.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This condition is seen in 40% to 60% of HIV positive patients.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is also the most common cause of loss of vision in these patients.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV/AIDS is diagnosed via laboratory testing and then staged based on the presence of certain signs or symptoms.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV screening is recommended by the United States Preventive Services Task Force for all people 15 years to 65 years of age, including all pregnant women.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Additionally, testing is recommended for those at high risk, which includes anyone diagnosed with a sexually transmitted illness.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In many areas of the world, a third of HIV carriers only discover they are infected at an advanced stage of the disease when AIDS or severe immunodeficiency has become apparent.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Most people infected with HIV develop seroconverted (antigen-specific) antibodies within three to twelve weeks after the initial infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Diagnosis of primary HIV before seroconversion is done by measuring HIV-RNA or p24 antigen.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Positive results obtained by antibody or PCR testing are confirmed either by a different antibody or by PCR.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Antibody tests in children younger than 18 months are typically inaccurate, due to the continued presence of maternal antibodies.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Thus HIV infection can only be diagnosed by PCR testing for HIV RNA or DNA, or via testing for the p24 antigen.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Much of the world lacks access to reliable PCR testing, and people in many places simply wait until either symptoms develop or the child is old enough for accurate antibody testing.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In sub-Saharan Africa between 2007 and 2009, between 30% and 70% of the population were aware of their HIV status.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In 2009, between 3.6% and 42% of men and women in sub-Saharan countries were tested; this represented a significant increase compared to previous years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Two main clinical staging systems are used to classify HIV and HIV-related disease for surveillance purposes: the WHO disease staging system for HIV infection and disease, and the CDC classification system for HIV infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The CDC's classification system is more frequently adopted in developed countries.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Since the WHO's staging system does not require laboratory tests, it is suited to the resource-restricted conditions encountered in developing countries, where it can also be used to help guide clinical management.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Despite their differences, the two systems allow a comparison for statistical purposes.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The World Health Organization first proposed a definition for AIDS in 1986.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Since then, the WHO classification has been updated and expanded several times, with the most recent version being published in 2007.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also created a classification system for HIV, and updated it in 2008 and 2014.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This system classifies HIV infections based on CD4 count and clinical symptoms, and describes the infection in five groups.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] For surveillance purposes, the AIDS diagnosis still stands even if, after treatment, the CD4+ T cell count rises to above 200 per μL of blood or other AIDS-defining illnesses are cured.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Consistent condom use reduces the risk of HIV transmission by approximately 80% over the long term.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] When condoms are used consistently by a couple in which one person is infected, the rate of HIV infection is less than 1% per year.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There is some evidence to suggest that female condoms may provide an equivalent level of protection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Application of a vaginal gel containing tenofovir (a reverse transcriptase inhibitor) immediately before sex seems to reduce infection rates by approximately 40% among African women.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] By contrast, use of the spermicide nonoxynol-9 may increase the risk of transmission due to its tendency to cause vaginal and rectal irritation.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Circumcision in sub-Saharan Africa "reduces the acquisition of HIV by heterosexual men by between 38% and 66% over 24 months".
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Owing to these studies, both the World Health Organization and UNAIDS recommended male circumcision in 2007 as a method of preventing female-to-male HIV transmission in areas with high rates of HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] However, whether it protects against male-to-female transmission is disputed, and whether it is of benefit in developed countries and among men who have sex with men is undetermined.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Programs encouraging sexual abstinence do not appear to affect subsequent HIV risk.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Evidence of any benefit from peer education is equally poor.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Comprehensive sexual education provided at school may decrease high-risk behavior.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] A substantial minority of young people continues to engage in high-risk practices despite knowing about HIV/AIDS, underestimating their own risk of becoming infected with HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Voluntary counseling and testing people for HIV does not affect risky behavior in those who test negative but does increase condom use in those who test positive.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Enhanced family planning services appear to increase the likelihood of women with HIV using contraception, compared to basic services.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is not known whether treating other sexually transmitted infections is effective in preventing HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Antiretroviral treatment among people with HIV whose CD4 count ≤ 550 cells/μL is a very effective way to prevent HIV infection of their partner (a strategy known as treatment as prevention, or TASP).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] TASP is associated with a 10- to 20-fold reduction in transmission risk.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV ("PrEP") with a daily dose of the medications tenofovir, with or without emtricitabine, is effective in people at high risk including men who have sex with men, couples where one is HIV-positive, and young heterosexuals in Africa.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It may also be effective in intravenous drug users, with a study finding a decrease in risk of 0.7 to 0.4 per 100 person years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The USPSTF, in 2019, recommended PrEP in those who are at high risk.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Universal precautions within the health care environment are believed to be effective in decreasing the risk of HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Intravenous drug use is an important risk factor, and harm reduction strategies such as needle-exchange programs and opioid substitution therapy appear effective in decreasing this risk.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] A course of antiretrovirals administered within 48 to 72 hours after exposure to HIV-positive blood or genital secretions is referred to as post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The use of the single agent zidovudine reduces the risk of an HIV infection five-fold following a needle-stick injury.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] As of 2013, the prevention regimen recommended in the United States consists of three medications—tenofovir, emtricitabine and raltegravir—as this may reduce the risk further.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] PEP treatment is recommended after a sexual assault when the perpetrator is known to be HIV-positive, but is controversial when their HIV status is unknown.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The duration of treatment is usually four weeks and is frequently associated with adverse effects—where zidovudine is used, about 70% of cases result in adverse effects such as nausea (24%), fatigue (22%), emotional distress (13%) and headaches (9%).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Programs to prevent the vertical transmission of HIV (from mothers to children) can reduce rates of transmission by 92–99%.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This primarily involves the use of a combination of antiviral medications during pregnancy and after birth in the infant, and potentially includes bottle feeding rather than breastfeeding.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If replacement feeding is acceptable, feasible, affordable, sustainable and safe, mothers should avoid breastfeeding their infants; however, exclusive breastfeeding is recommended during the first months of life if this is not the case.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If exclusive breastfeeding is carried out, the provision of extended antiretroviral prophylaxis to the infant decreases the risk of transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eradicate mother-to-child transmission of HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Currently there is no licensed vaccine for HIV or AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The most effective vaccine trial to date, RV 144, was published in 2009; it found a partial reduction in the risk of transmission of roughly 30%, stimulating some hope in the research community of developing a truly effective vaccine.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV/AIDS is a chronic condition, as there is currently no cure.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Treatment consists of highly active antiretroviral therapy (ART), which slows progression of the disease.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] As of 2025, 40.9 million people globally were living with HIV, and 32.1 million people were accessing ART.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Treatment also includes preventive and active treatment of opportunistic infections.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] As of July 2022, four people have been successfully cleared of HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Rapid initiation of antiretroviral therapy within one week of diagnosis appear to improve treatment outcomes in low and medium-income settings and is recommend for newly diagnosed HIV patients.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV retinopathy was a very common cause of blindness in people with AIDS before the introduction of highly active antiretroviral therapy, but its incidence is declining due to proper and timely management of AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Even if there are signs of retinopathy, it may reverse as CD4+ T cell counts increase.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Reversal of HIV retinopathy is a helpful sign of positive response to antiretroviral therapy in AIDS patients.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] But if HIV treatment is delayed it may lead to permanent visual loss.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Occurrence of HIV retinopathy may also be an indicator of therapeutic failure in AIDS patients undergoing treatment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Current ART options are combinations (or "cocktails") consisting of at least three medications belonging to at least two types, or "classes", of antiretroviral agents.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There are also two drugs, ritonavir (RTV) and cobicistat (COBI) which can be used as pharmacokinetic (PK) enhancers (or boosters) to improve the PK profiles of PIs and the INSTI elvitegravir (EVG).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The World Health Organization and the United States recommend antiretrovirals in people of all ages (including pregnant women) as soon as the diagnosis is made, regardless of CD4 count.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Once treatment is begun, it is recommended that it is continued without breaks or "holidays".
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Many people are diagnosed only after treatment ideally should have begun.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The desired outcome of treatment is a long-term plasma HIV-RNA count below 50 copies/mL.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Levels to determine if treatment is effective are initially recommended after four weeks and once levels fall below 50 copies/mL checks every three to six months are typically adequate.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Inadequate control is deemed to be greater than 400 copies/mL.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Based on these criteria treatment is effective in more than 95% of people during the first year.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Benefits of treatment include a decreased risk of progression to AIDS and a decreased risk of death.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the developing world, treatment also improves physical and mental health.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] With treatment, there is a 70% reduced risk of acquiring tuberculosis.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Additional benefits include a decreased risk of transmission of the disease to sexual partners and a decrease in mother-to-child transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The effectiveness of treatment depends to a large part on compliance.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Reasons for non-adherence to treatment include poor access to medical care, inadequate social supports, mental illness and drug abuse.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The complexity of treatment regimens (due to pill numbers and dosing frequency) and adverse effects may reduce adherence.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Even though cost is an important issue with some medications, 47% of those who needed them were taking them in low- and middle-income countries as of 2010, and the rate of adherence is similar in low-income and high-income countries.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Specific adverse events are related to the antiretroviral agent taken.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Some relatively common adverse events include: lipodystrophy syndrome, dyslipidemia, and diabetes mellitus, especially with protease inhibitors.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Other common symptoms include diarrhea, and an increased risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Newer recommended treatments are associated with fewer adverse effects.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Certain medications may be associated with birth defects and therefore may be unsuitable for women hoping to have children.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Treatment recommendations for children are somewhat different from those for adults.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The World Health Organization recommends treating all children less than five years of age; children above five are treated like adults.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The United States guidelines recommend treating all children less than 12 months of age and all those with HIV RNA counts greater than 100,000 copies/mL between one year and five years of age.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In 2020, the European Medicines Agency recommended approval of a long-acting injectable combination of the antiretrovirals rilpivirine and cabotegravir, marketed as Rekambys and Vocabria; unlike standard daily pills, it is administered by intramuscular injection every one to two months.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is indicated as maintenance therapy for adults who are already virologically suppressed (viral load below 50 copies/mL) on a stable regimen, with no documented resistance to non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors or integrase strand transfer inhibitors.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Measures to prevent opportunistic infections are effective in many people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In addition to improving current disease, treatment with antiretrovirals reduces the risk of developing additional opportunistic infections.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Adults and adolescents who are living with HIV (even on anti-retroviral therapy) with no evidence of active tuberculosis in settings with high tuberculosis burden should receive isoniazid preventive therapy (IPT); the tuberculin skin test can be used to help decide if IPT is needed.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Children with HIV may benefit from screening for tuberculosis.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Vaccination against hepatitis A and B is advised for all people at risk of HIV before they become infected; however, it may also be given after infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis between four and six weeks of age, and ceasing breastfeeding of infants born to HIV-positive mothers, is recommended in resource-limited settings.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] It is also recommended to prevent PCP when a person's CD4 count is below 200 cells/uL and in those who have or have previously had PCP.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] People with substantial immunosuppression are also advised to receive prophylactic therapy for toxoplasmosis and MAC.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Appropriate preventive measures reduced the rate of these infections by 50% between 1992 and 1997.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Influenza vaccination and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine are often recommended in people with HIV/AIDS with some evidence of benefit.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) has issued recommendations regarding nutrient requirements in HIV/AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Dietary intake of micronutrients at RDA levels by HIV-infected adults is recommended by the WHO; higher intake of vitamin A, zinc, and iron can produce adverse effects in HIV-positive adults, and is not recommended unless there is documented deficiency.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Dietary supplementation for people who are infected with HIV and who have inadequate nutrition or dietary deficiencies may strengthen their immune systems or help them recover from infections; however, evidence indicating an overall benefit in morbidity or reduction in mortality is not consistent.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] People with HIV/AIDS are up to four times more likely to develop type 2 diabetes than those who are not tested positive with the virus.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Evidence for supplementation with selenium is mixed with some tentative evidence of benefit.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] For pregnant and lactating women with HIV, multivitamin supplement improves outcomes for both mothers and children.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If the pregnant or lactating mother has been advised to take anti-retroviral medication to prevent mother-to-child HIV transmission, multivitamin supplements should not replace these treatments.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There is some evidence that vitamin A supplementation in children with an HIV infection reduces mortality and improves growth.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the US, approximately 60% of people with HIV use various forms of complementary or alternative medicine, whose effectiveness has not been established.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There is not enough evidence to support the use of herbal medicines.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There is insufficient evidence to recommend or support the use of medical cannabis to try to increase appetite or weight gain.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV/AIDS has become a chronic rather than an acutely fatal disease in many areas of the world.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Prognosis varies between people, and both the CD4 count and viral load are useful for predicted outcomes.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Without treatment, average survival time after infection with HIV is estimated to be 9 to 11 years, depending on the HIV subtype.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] After the diagnosis of AIDS, if treatment is not available, survival ranges between 6 and 19 months.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] ART and appropriate prevention of opportunistic infections reduces the death rate by 80%, and raises the life expectancy for a newly diagnosed young adult to 20–50 years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This is between two thirds and nearly that of the general population.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] If treatment is started late in the infection, prognosis is not as good: for example, if treatment is begun following the diagnosis of AIDS, life expectancy is ~10–40 years.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Half of infants born with HIV die before two years of age without treatment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The primary causes of death from HIV/AIDS are opportunistic infections and cancer, both of which are frequently the result of the progressive failure of the immune system.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Risk of cancer appears to increase once the CD4 count is below 500/μL.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Tuberculosis co-infection is one of the leading causes of sickness and death in those with HIV/AIDS being present in a third of all HIV-infected people and causing 25% of HIV-related deaths.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV is also one of the most important risk factors for tuberculosis.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Hepatitis C is another very common co-infection where each disease increases the progression of the other.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The two most common cancers associated with HIV/AIDS are Kaposi's sarcoma and AIDS-related non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Other cancers that are more frequent include anal cancer, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Even with anti-retroviral treatment, over the long term HIV-infected people may experience neurocognitive disorders, osteoporosis, neuropathy, cancers, nephropathy, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Some conditions, such as lipodystrophy, may be caused both by HIV and its treatment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a global pandemic.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] As of 2025, approximately 40.9 million people worldwide are living with HIV, the number of new infections that year being about 1.2 million.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This is down 43% from 2.1 million new infections in 2010.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Among new infections, 41% are in women and girls globally.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There were [CONFIRM 2025 figure] AIDS-related deaths in 2025, down from a peak of 2 million in 2005.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Among persons living with HIV (PLWH), the largest proportion reside in eastern and southern Africa (20.6 million, 54.6%).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] This region also had the highest rate of adult and child deaths due to AIDS in 2020 (310,000, 46.6%).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Sub-Saharan African adolescent girls and young women (aged 15–24 years) account for 77% of new infections among this age-range globally.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Here, in contrast to other regions, adolescent girls and young women are three times more likely to acquire HIV than age-matched males.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Despite these statistics, overall, new HIV infections and AIDS-related deaths have substantially decreased in this region since 2010.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Eastern Europe and central Asia has observed a 43% increase in new HIV infections and 32% increase in AIDS-related deaths since 2010, the highest of all global regions.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] These infections are predominantly distributed in persons who inject drugs, with gay men and other men who have sex with men or persons who engage in transaction sex the second and third populations most impacted in this region.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] At the end of 2019, United States indicated that approximately 1.2 million people aged ≥13 years were living with HIV, resulting in about 18,500 deaths in 2020.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] There were 34,800 estimated new infections in the US in 2019, 53% of which were in the southern region of the country.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In addition to geographic location, significant disparities in HIV incidence exist among men, Black or Hispanic populations, and men who reported male-to-male sexual contact.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimated that in that year, 158,500 people or 13% of infected Americans were unaware of their infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In the United Kingdom as of 2015, there were approximately 101,200 cases which resulted in 594 deaths.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] In Canada as of 2008, there were about 65,000 cases causing 53 deaths.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Between the first recognition of AIDS (in 1981) and 2009, it has led to nearly 30 million deaths.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Rates of HIV are lowest in North Africa and the Middle East (0.1% or less), East Asia (0.1%), and Western and Central Europe (0.2%).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] The worst-affected European countries, in 2009 and 2012 estimates, are Russia, Ukraine, Latvia, Moldova, Portugal and Belarus, in decreasing order of prevalence.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Groups at higher risk of acquiring HIV include persons who engage in transactional sex, gay men and other men who have sex with men, persons who inject drugs, transgender persons, and those who are incarcerated or detained.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p01] Climate change impacts HIV risk and the availability of and access to HIV prevention and treatment services, and can contribute to poor nutrition, impaired immunity, and poor adherence to treatment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The first news story on the disease appeared on May 18, 1981, in the gay newspaper *New York Native*.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] AIDS was first clinically reported on June 5, 1981, with five cases in the United States.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The initial cases were a cluster of injecting drug users and gay men with no known cause of impaired immunity who showed symptoms of *Pneumocystis carinii* pneumonia (PCP), a rare opportunistic infection that was known to occur in people with very compromised immune systems.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Soon thereafter, a large number of homosexual men developed a generally rare skin cancer called Kaposi's sarcoma (KS).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Many more cases of PCP and KS emerged, alerting the U.S.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and a CDC task force was formed to monitor the outbreak.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In the early days, the CDC did not have an official name for the disease, often referring to it by way of diseases associated with it, such as lymphadenopathy, the disease after which the discoverers of HIV originally named the virus.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] They also used *Kaposi's sarcoma and opportunistic infections*, the name by which a task force had been set up in 1981.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] At one point the CDC referred to it as the "4H disease", as the syndrome seemed to affect heroin users, homosexuals, hemophiliacs, and Haitians.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The term *GRID*, which stood for gay-related immune deficiency, had also been coined.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] However, after determining that AIDS was not isolated to the gay community, it was realized that the term *GRID* was misleading, and the term *AIDS* was introduced at a meeting in July 1982.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] By September 1982 the CDC started referring to the disease as AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In 1983, two separate research groups led by Robert Gallo and Luc Montagnier declared that a novel retrovirus may have been infecting people with AIDS, and published their findings in the same issue of the journal *Science*.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Gallo claimed a virus which his group had isolated from a person with AIDS was strikingly similar in shape to other human T-lymphotropic viruses (HTLVs) that his group had been the first to isolate.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Gallo's group called their newly isolated virus HTLV-III.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] At the same time, Montagnier's group isolated a virus from a person presenting with swelling of the lymph nodes of the neck and physical weakness, two characteristic symptoms of AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Contradicting the report from Gallo's group, Montagnier and his colleagues showed that core proteins of this virus were immunologically different from those of HTLV-I.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Montagnier's group named their isolated virus lymphadenopathy-associated virus (LAV).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] As these two viruses turned out to be the same, in 1986, LAV and HTLV-III were renamed HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The origin of HIV / AIDS and the circumstances that led to its emergence remain unsolved.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Both HIV-1 and HIV-2 are believed to have originated in non-human primates in West-central Africa and were transferred to humans in the early 20th century.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] HIV-1 appears to have originated in southern Cameroon through the evolution of SIV(cpz), a simian immunodeficiency virus (SIV) that infects wild chimpanzees (HIV-1 descends from the SIVcpz endemic in the chimpanzee subspecies *Pan troglodytes troglodytes*).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The closest relative of HIV-2 is SIV (smm), a virus of the sooty mangabey (*Cercocebus atys atys*), an Old World monkey living in coastal West Africa (from southern Senegal to western Ivory Coast).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] New World monkeys such as the owl monkey are resistant to HIV-1 infection, possibly because of a genomic fusion of two viral resistance genes.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] HIV-1 is thought to have jumped the species barrier on at least three separate occasions, giving rise to the three groups of the virus, M, N, and O.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] There is evidence that humans who participate in bushmeat activities, either as hunters or as bushmeat vendors, commonly acquire SIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] However, SIV is a weak virus which is typically suppressed by the human immune system within weeks of infection.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] It is thought that several transmissions of the virus from individual to individual in quick succession are necessary to allow it enough time to mutate into HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Furthermore, due to its relatively low person-to-person transmission rate, SIV can only spread throughout the population in the presence of one or more high-risk transmission channels, which are thought to have been absent in Africa before the 20th century.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Specific proposed high-risk transmission channels, allowing the virus to adapt to humans and spread throughout society, depend on the proposed timing of the animal-to-human crossing.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Genetic studies of the virus suggest that the most recent common ancestor of the HIV-1 M group dates back to c.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] While transmission rates of HIV during vaginal intercourse are low under regular circumstances, they are increased manyfold if one of the partners has a sexually transmitted infection causing genital ulcers.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] An alternative view holds that unsafe medical practices in Africa after World War II, such as unsterile reuse of single-use syringes during mass vaccination, antibiotic and anti-malaria treatment campaigns, were the initial vector that allowed the virus to adapt to humans and spread.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The earliest well-documented case of HIV in a human dates back to 1959 in the Congo.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The virus may have been present in the U.S. as early as the mid-to-late 1950s.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] A 16-year-old male named Robert Rayford presented with symptoms in 1966 and died in 1969.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In the 1970s, there were cases of people getting parasites and becoming sick with what was then called "gay bowel disease" but is now suspected to have been AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The earliest retrospectively described case of AIDS is believed to have been in Norway beginning in 1966, that of Arvid Noe.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In July 1960, in the wake of Congo's independence, the United Nations recruited Francophone experts and technicians from all over the world to assist in filling administrative gaps left by Belgium, who did not leave behind an African elite to run the country.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] By 1962, Haitians made up the second-largest group of well-educated experts (out of the 48 national groups recruited), that totaled around 4,500 in the country.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Jacques Pépin, a Canadian author of *The Origins of AIDS*, stipulates that Haiti was one of HIV's entry points to the U.S. and that a Haitian may have carried HIV back across the Atlantic in the 1960s.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The epidemic rapidly spread among high-risk groups (initially, sexually promiscuous men who have sex with men).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] By 1978, the prevalence of HIV-1 among gay male residents of New York City and San Francisco was estimated at 5%, suggesting that several thousand individuals in the country had been infected.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Stigma-related violence or the fear of violence prevents many people from seeking HIV testing, returning for their results, or securing treatment, possibly turning what could be a manageable chronic illness into a death sentence and perpetuating the spread of HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Often, AIDS stigma is expressed in conjunction with one or more other stigmas, particularly those associated with homosexuality, bisexuality, promiscuity, prostitution, and intravenous drug use.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In many developed countries, there is an association between AIDS and homosexuality or bisexuality, and this association is correlated with higher levels of sexual prejudice, such as anti-homosexual or anti-bisexual attitudes.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] There is also a perceived association between AIDS and all male-male sexual behavior, including sex between uninfected men.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] However, the dominant mode of spread worldwide for HIV remains heterosexual transmission.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt was conceived in 1985 to celebrate the lives of those who had died of AIDS when stigma prevented many from receiving funerals.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] It is now cared for by the National AIDS Memorial in San Francisco.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In 2003, as part of an overall reform of marriage and population legislation, it became legal for those diagnosed with AIDS to marry in China.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Between 2004 and 2020, Somen Debnath has travelled the world by bicycle promoting HIV / AIDS awareness.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] National Library of Medicine developed a traveling exhibition titled *Surviving and Thriving: AIDS, Politics, and Culture*; this covered medical research, the U.S. government's response, and personal stories from people with AIDS, caregivers, and activists.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Stigma has proved an obstacle to the update of PrEP.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Within the MSM community, the greatest barrier to PrEP use has been the stigma surrounding HIV and gay men.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Gay men on PrEP have experienced "slut-shaming".
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Numerous other barriers have been identified, including lack of quality LGBTQ care, cost, and adherence to medication use.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] HIV/AIDS affects the economics of both individuals and countries.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The gross domestic product of the most affected countries has decreased due to the lack of human capital.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Without proper nutrition, health care and medicine, large numbers of people die from AIDS-related complications.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Before death they will not only be unable to work, but will also require significant medical care.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] It is estimated that as of 2007 there were 12 million AIDS orphans.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Many are cared for by elderly grandparents.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Returning to work after beginning treatment for HIV/AIDS is difficult, and affected people often work less than the average worker.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Unemployment in people with HIV/AIDS also is associated with suicidal ideation, memory problems, and social isolation.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Employment increases self-esteem, sense of dignity, confidence, and quality of life for people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Anti-retroviral treatment may help people with HIV/AIDS work more, and may increase the chance that a person with HIV/AIDS will be employed (low-quality evidence).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] By affecting mainly young adults, AIDS reduces the taxable population, in turn reducing the resources available for public expenditures such as education and health services not related to AIDS, resulting in increasing pressure on the state's finances and slower growth of the economy.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] This causes a slower growth of the tax base, an effect that is reinforced if there are growing expenditures on treating the sick, training (to replace sick workers), sick pay, and caring for AIDS orphans.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] This is especially true if the sharp increase in adult mortality shifts the responsibility from the family to the government in caring for these orphans.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] At the household level, AIDS causes both loss of income and increased spending on healthcare.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] A study in Côte d'Ivoire showed that households having a person with HIV/AIDS spent twice as much on medical expenses as other households.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] This additional expenditure also leaves less income to spend on education and other personal or family investment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The topic of religion and AIDS has become highly controversial, primarily because some religious authorities have publicly declared their opposition to the use of condoms.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Some religious organizations have claimed that prayer can cure HIV/AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In 2011, the BBC reported that some churches in London were claiming that prayer would cure AIDS, and the Hackney-based Centre for the Study of Sexual Health and HIV reported that several people stopped taking their medication, sometimes on the direct advice of their pastor, leading to many deaths.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] The Synagogue Church Of All Nations advertised an "anointing water" to promote God's healing, although the group denies advising people to stop taking medication.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] One of the first high-profile cases of AIDS was the American gay actor Rock Hudson.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] He had been diagnosed during 1984, announced that he had had the virus on July 25, 1985, and died a few months later on October 2, 1985.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Another notable British casualty of AIDS that year was Nicholas Eden, a gay politician and son of former prime minister Anthony Eden.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] On November 24, 1991, British rock star Freddie Mercury died from an AIDS-related illness, having revealed the diagnosis only on the previous day.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] One of the first high-profile heterosexual cases of the virus was American tennis player Arthur Ashe.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] He was diagnosed as HIV-positive on August 31, 1988, having contracted the virus from blood transfusions during heart surgery earlier in the 1980s.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Further tests within 24 hours of the initial diagnosis revealed that Ashe had AIDS, but he did not tell the public about his diagnosis until April 1992.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] He died as a result on February 6, 1993, aged 49.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Therese Frare's photograph of gay activist David Kirby, as he lay dying from AIDS while surrounded by family, was taken in April 1990.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] *Life* magazine said the photo became the one image "most powerfully identified with the HIV/AIDS epidemic." The photo was displayed in *Life*, was the winner of the World Press Photo, and acquired worldwide notoriety after being used in a United Colors of Benetton advertising campaign in 1992.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Many famous artists and AIDS activists such as Larry Kramer, Diamanda Galás and Rosa von Praunheim campaign for AIDS education and the rights of those affected.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] These artists worked with various media formats.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Criminal transmission of HIV is the intentional or reckless infection of a person with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Some countries or jurisdictions, including some areas of the United States, have laws that criminalize HIV transmission or exposure.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Others may charge the accused under laws enacted before the HIV pandemic.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In 1996, Ugandan-born Canadian Johnson Aziga was diagnosed with HIV; he subsequently had unprotected sex with eleven women without disclosing his diagnosis.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] By 2003, seven had contracted HIV; two died from complications related to AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Aziga was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] There are many misconceptions about HIV and AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Three misconceptions are that AIDS can spread through casual contact, that sexual intercourse with a virgin will cure AIDS, and that HIV can infect only gay men and drug users.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] In 2014, some among the British public wrongly thought one could get HIV from kissing (16%), sharing a glass (5%), spitting (16%), a public toilet seat (4%), and coughing or sneezing (5%).
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Other misconceptions are that any act of anal intercourse between two uninfected gay men can lead to HIV infection, and that open discussion of HIV and homosexuality in schools will lead to increased rates of AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] A small group of individuals continue to dispute the connection between HIV and AIDS, the existence of HIV itself, or the validity of HIV testing and treatment methods.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] These claims, known as AIDS denialism, have been examined and rejected by the scientific community.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Several discredited conspiracy theories have held that HIV was created by scientists, either inadvertently or deliberately.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Operation INFEKTION was a worldwide Soviet active measures operation to spread the claim that the United States had created HIV/AIDS.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Surveys show that a significant number of people believed—and continue to believe—in such claims.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] HIV/AIDS research includes all medical research which attempts to prevent, treat, or cure HIV/AIDS, along with fundamental research about the nature of HIV as an infectious agent, and about AIDS as the disease caused by HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Many governments and research institutions participate in HIV/AIDS research.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] This research includes behavioral health interventions such as sex education, and drug development, such as research into microbicides for sexually transmitted diseases, HIV vaccines, and antiretroviral drugs.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Other medical research areas include the topics of pre-exposure prophylaxis, post-exposure prophylaxis, and circumcision and HIV.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Public health officials, researchers, and programs can gain a more comprehensive picture of the barriers they face, and the efficacy of current approaches to HIV treatment and prevention, by tracking standard HIV indicators.
[src:t-cell/acquired-immune-deficiency-syndrome-p02] Use of common indicators is an increasing focus of development organizations and researchers.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The **adaptive immune system** (**AIS**), also known as the **acquired immune system** or **specific immune system**, is a subsystem of the immune system that is composed of specialized cells, organs, and processes that eliminate pathogens specifically.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune system is one of the two main immunity strategies found in vertebrates (the other being the innate immune system).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Like the innate system, the adaptive immune system includes both humoral immunity components and cell-mediated immunity components and destroys invading pathogens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Unlike the innate immune system, which is pre-programmed to react to common broad categories of pathogen, the adaptive immune system is highly specific to each particular pathogen the body has encountered.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Adaptive immunity creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to future encounters with that pathogen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies are a critical part of the adaptive immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Adaptive immunity can provide long-lasting protection, sometimes for the person's entire lifetime.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] For example, someone who recovers from measles is now protected against measles for their lifetime; in other cases it does not provide lifetime protection, as with chickenpox.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This process of adaptive immunity is the basis of vaccination.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The cells that carry out the adaptive immune response are white blood cells known as lymphocytes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] B cells and T cells, two different types of lymphocytes, carry out the main activities: antibody responses, and cell-mediated immune response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In antibody responses, B cells are activated to secrete antibodies, which are proteins also known as immunoglobulins.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies travel through the bloodstream and bind to the foreign antigen causing it to inactivate, which does not allow the antigen to bind to the host.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Antigens are any substances that elicit the adaptive immune response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Sometimes the adaptive system is unable to distinguish harmful from harmless foreign molecules; the effects of this may be hayfever, asthma, or any other allergy.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In adaptive immunity, pathogen-specific receptors are "acquired" during the lifetime of the organism (whereas in innate immunity pathogen-specific receptors are already encoded in the genome).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This acquired response is called "adaptive" because it prepares the body's immune system for future challenges (though it can actually also be maladaptive when it results in allergies or autoimmunity).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The system is highly adaptable because of two factors.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] First, somatic hypermutation is a process of accelerated random genetic mutations in the antibody-coding genes, which allows antibodies with novel specificity to be created.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Second, V(D)J recombination randomly selects one variable (V), one diversity (D), and one joining (J) region for genetic recombination and discards the rest, which produces a highly unique combination of antigen-receptor gene segments in each lymphocyte.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This mechanism allows a small number of genetic segments to generate a vast number of different antigen receptors, which are then uniquely expressed on each individual lymphocyte.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Since the gene rearrangement leads to an irreversible change in the DNA of each cell, all progeny (offspring) of that cell inherit genes that encode the same receptor specificity, including the memory B cells and memory T cells that are the keys to long-lived specific immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The term "adaptive" was first used by Robert Good in reference to antibody responses in frogs as a synonym for "acquired immune response" in 1964.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Good acknowledged he used the terms as synonyms but explained only that he preferred to use the term "adaptive".
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The term "adaptive" as used in immunology is problematic as acquired immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the physiological sense.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Indeed, both acquired and innate immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the evolutionary sense.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Most textbooks today, following the early use by Janeway, use "adaptive" almost exclusively and noting in glossaries that the term is synonymous with "acquired".
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The classic sense of "acquired immunity" came to mean, since Tonegawa's discovery, "antigen-specific immunity mediated by somatic gene rearrangements that create clone-defining antigen receptors".
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In the last decade, the term "adaptive" has been increasingly applied to another class of immune response not so-far associated with somatic gene rearrangements.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These include expansion of natural killer (NK) cells with so-far unexplained specificity for antigens, expansion of NK cells expressing germ-line encoded receptors, and activation of other innate immune cells to an activated state that confers a short-term "immune memory".
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In this sense, "adaptive immunity" more closely resembles the concept of "activated state" or "heterostasis", thus returning in sense to the physiological sense of "adaptation" to environmental changes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Acquired immunity is triggered in vertebrates when a pathogen evades the innate immune system and (1) generates a threshold level of antigen and (2) generates "stranger" or "danger" signals activating dendritic cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In humans, it takes 4–7 days for the adaptive immune system to mount a significant response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] T and B lymphocytes are the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The human body has about 2 trillion lymphocytes, which are 20–40% of white blood cells; their total mass is about the same as the brain or liver.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The peripheral bloodstream contains only 2% of all circulating lymphocytes; the other 98% move within tissues and the lymphatic system, which includes the lymph nodes and spleen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In humans, approximately 1–2% of the lymphocyte pool recirculates each hour to increase the opportunity for the cells to encounter the specific pathogen and antigen that they react to.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] B cells and T cells are derived from the same multipotent hematopoietic stem cells, and look identical to one another until after they are activated.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] B cells play a large role in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are intimately involved in cell-mediated immune responses.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In all vertebrates except Agnatha, B cells and T cells are produced by stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] T cell progenitors then migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they develop further.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Acquired immunity relies on the capacity of immune cells to distinguish between the body's own cells and unwanted invaders.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The host's cells express "self" antigens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These antigens are different from those on the surface of bacteria or on the surface of virus-infected host cells ("non-self" or "foreign" antigens).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune response is triggered by recognizing foreign antigen in the cellular context of an activated dendritic cell.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), all cells are capable of presenting antigen through the function of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Some cells are specially equipped to present antigen, and to prime naive T cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Dendritic cells, B-cells, and macrophages are equipped with special "co-stimulatory" ligands recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on T cells, and are termed professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Several T cells subgroups can be activated by professional APCs, and each type of T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique toxin or microbial pathogen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The type of T cell activated, and the type of response generated, depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Dendritic cells engulf exogenous pathogens, such as bacteria, parasites or toxins in the tissues and then migrate, via chemotactic signals, to the T cell-enriched lymph nodes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] During migration, dendritic cells undergo a process of maturation in which they lose most of their ability to engulf other pathogens, and develop an ability to communicate with T-cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The dendritic cell uses enzymes to chop the pathogen into smaller pieces, called antigens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In the lymph node, the dendritic cell displays these non-self antigens on its surface by coupling them to a receptor called the major histocompatibility complex, or MHC (also known in humans as human leukocyte antigen (HLA)).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This MHC-antigen complex is recognized by T-cells passing through the lymph node.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Exogenous antigens are usually displayed on MHC class II molecules, which activate CD4+T helper cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Endogenous antigens are produced by intracellular bacteria and viruses replicating within a host cell.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The host cell uses enzymes to digest virally associated proteins and displays these pieces on its surface to T-cells by coupling them to MHC.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Endogenous antigens are typically displayed on MHC class I molecules, and activate CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), MHC class I is expressed by all host cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as TC, cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), or killer T cells) are a sub-group of T cells that induce the death of cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Naive cytotoxic T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor (TCR) strongly interacts with a peptide-bound MHC class I molecule.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This affinity depends on the type and orientation of the antigen/MHC complex, and is what keeps the CTL and infected cell bound together.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Once activated, the CTL undergoes a process called clonal selection, in which it gains functions and divides rapidly to produce an army of "armed" effector cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The activated CTL then travels throughout the body searching for cells that bear that unique MHC class I + peptide.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] When exposed to these infected or dysfunctional somatic cells, effector CTLs release perforin and granulysin: cytotoxins that form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions and water to flow into the infected cell and causing it to burst or lyse.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] CTLs release granzyme, a serine protease encapsulated in a granule that enters cells via pores to induce apoptosis (cell death).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] To limit extensive tissue damage during an infection, CTL activation is tightly controlled and in general requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T-cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] On resolution of the infection, most effector cells die and phagocytes clear them away—but a few of these cells remain as memory cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] On a later encounter with the same antigen, these memory cells quickly differentiate into effector cells, dramatically shortening the time required to mount an effective response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] CD4+ lymphocytes, also called "helper" T cells, are immune response mediators, and play an important role in establishing and maximizing the capabilities of the acquired immune response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These cells have no cytotoxic or phagocytic activity; and cannot kill infected cells or clear pathogens, but, in essence "manage" the immune response, by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Helper T cells express T cell receptors (TCR) that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The activation of a naive helper T-cell causes it to release cytokines, which influences the activity of many cell types, including the APC (Antigen-Presenting Cell) that activated it.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Helper T-cells require a much milder activation stimulus than cytotoxic T cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Helper T cells can provide extra signals that "help" activate cytotoxic cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Classically, two types of effector CD4+ T helper cell responses can be induced by a professional APC, designated Th1 and Th2, each designed to eliminate different types of pathogens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The factors that dictate whether an infection triggers a Th1 or Th2 type response are not fully understood, but the response generated does play an important role in the clearance of different pathogens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The Th1 response is characterized by the production of Interferon-gamma, which activates the bactericidal activities of macrophages, and induces B cells to make opsonizing (marking for phagocytosis) and complement-fixing antibodies, and leads to *cell-mediated immunity*.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In general, Th1 responses are more effective against intracellular pathogens (viruses and bacteria that are inside host cells).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The Th2 response is characterized by the release of Interleukin 5, which induces eosinophils in the clearance of parasites.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Th2 also produce Interleukin 4, which facilitates B cell isotype switching.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In general, Th2 responses are more effective against extracellular bacteria, parasites including helminths and toxins.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Like cytotoxic T cells, most of the CD4+ helper cells die on resolution of infection, with a few remaining as CD4+ memory cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Increasingly, there is strong evidence from mouse and human-based scientific studies of a broader diversity in CD4+ effector T helper cell subsets.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Regulatory T (Treg) cells, have been identified as important negative regulators of adaptive immunity as they limit and suppress the immune system to control aberrant immune responses to self-antigens; an important mechanism in controlling the development of autoimmune diseases.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Follicular helper T (Tfh) cells are another distinct population of effector CD4+ T cells that develop from naive T cells post-antigen activation.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Tfh cells are specialized in helping B cell humoral immunity as they are uniquely capable of migrating to follicular B cells in secondary lymphoid organs and provide them positive paracrine signals to enable the generation and recall production of high-quality affinity-matured antibodies.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Similar to Tregs, Tfh cells also play a role in immunological tolerance as an abnormal expansion of Tfh cell numbers can lead to unrestricted autoreactive antibody production causing severe systemic autoimmune disorders.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The relevance of CD4+ T helper cells is highlighted during an HIV infection.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] HIV is able to subvert the immune system by specifically attacking the CD4+ T cells, precisely the cells that could drive the clearance of the virus, but also the cells that drive immunity against all other pathogens encountered during an organism's lifetime.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ αβ T cells and share characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and natural killer cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells exhibit characteristics that place them at the border between innate and acquired immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] On one hand, γδ T cells may be considered a component of adaptive immunity in that they rearrange TCR genes via V(D)J recombination, which also produces junctional diversity, and develop a memory phenotype.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] On the other hand, however, the various subsets may also be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] B Cells are the major cells involved in the creation of antibodies that circulate in blood plasma and lymph, known as humoral immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies (also known as immunoglobulin, Ig), are large Y-shaped proteins used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In mammals, there are five types of antibody: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, differing in biological properties; each has evolved to handle different kinds of antigens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Upon activation, B cells produce antibodies, each of which recognize a unique antigen, and neutralizing specific pathogens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Like the T cell, B cells express a unique B cell receptor (BCR), in this case, a membrane-bound antibody molecule.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] All the BCR of any one clone of B cells recognizes and binds to only one particular antigen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] A critical difference between B cells and T cells is how each cell "sees" an antigen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] T cells recognize their cognate antigen in a processed form – as a peptide in the context of an MHC molecule, whereas B cells recognize antigens in their native form.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Once a B cell encounters its cognate (or specific) antigen (and receives additional signals from a helper T cell (predominately Th2 type)), it further differentiates into an effector cell, known as a plasma cell.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Plasma cells are short-lived cells (2–3 days) that secrete antibodies.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These antibodies bind to antigens, making them easier targets for phagocytes, and trigger the complement cascade.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] About 10% of plasma cells survive to become long-lived antigen-specific memory B cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Already primed to produce specific antibodies, these cells can be called upon to respond quickly if the same pathogen re-infects the host, while the host experiences few, if any, symptoms.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish, have an adaptive immune system that shows 3 different cell lineages, each sharing a common origin with B cells, αβ T cells, and innate-like γΔ T cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Instead of the classical antibodies and T cell receptors, these animals possess a large array of molecules called variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs for short) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] For a long time it was thought that insects and other invertebrates possess only innate immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] However, in recent years some of the basic hallmarks of adaptive immunity have been discovered in insects.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Those traits are immune memory and specificity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Although the hallmarks are present the mechanisms are different from those in vertebrates.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Immune memory in insects was discovered through the phenomenon of priming.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] When insects are exposed to non-lethal dose or heat killed bacteria they are able to develop a memory of that infection that allows them to withstand otherwise lethal dose of the same bacteria they were exposed to before.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Unlike in vertebrates, insects do not possess cells specific for adaptive immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Instead those mechanisms are mediated by hemocytes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Hemocytes function similarly to phagocytes and after priming they are able to more effectively recognize and engulf the pathogen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] It was also shown that it is possible to transfer the memory into offspring.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] For example, in honeybees if the queen is infected with bacteria then the newly born workers have enhanced abilities in fighting with the same bacteria.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Other experimental model based on red flour beetle also showed pathogen specific primed memory transfer into offspring from both mothers and fathers.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The most commonly accepted theory of this specificity is based on the *Dscam* gene.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The *Dscam* gene, which mediates phagocytosis in some insects, contains three variable Ig domains.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These domains can be alternatively spliced, producing a large number of possible isoforms.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] It has been shown that after exposure to different pathogens, different isoforms of Dscam are produced, and that these isoforms associate and defend against bacteria in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Another mechanism that supports the specificity of insect immunity is RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] RNAi is a form of antiviral immunity with high specificity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] It has several different pathways that all end with the virus being unable to replicate.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] One of the pathways is siRNA in which long double stranded RNA is cut into pieces that serve as templates for protein complex Ago2-RISC that finds and degrades complementary RNA of the virus.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] MiRNA pathway in cytoplasm binds to Ago1-RISC complex and functions as a template for viral RNA degradation.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Last one is piRNA where small RNA binds to the Piwi protein family and controls transposones and other mobile elements.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Despite the research the exact mechanisms responsible for immune priming and specificity in insects are not well described.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] CRISPR has a lot of short repeated sequences.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These sequences are part of an adaptive immune system for prokaryotes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] It allows them to remember and counter the bacteriophages which prey on them.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] They work as a kind of acquired immune system for bacteria.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] When B cells and T cells are activated some become memory B cells and some memory T cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Throughout the lifetime of an animal these memory cells form a database of effective B and T lymphocytes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Upon interaction with a previously encountered antigen, the appropriate memory cells are selected and activated.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In this manner, the second and subsequent exposures to an antigen produce a stronger and faster immune response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This is "adaptive" in the sense that the body's immune system prepares itself for future challenges, but is "maladaptive" of course if the receptors are autoimmune.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Immunological memory can be in the form of either *passive* short-term memory or *active* long-term memory.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Passive memory is usually short-term, lasting between a few days and several months.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Newborn infants have had no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] *In utero*, maternal IgG is transported directly across the placenta, so that, at birth, human babies have high levels of antibodies, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Breast milk contains antibodies (mainly IgA) that are transferred to the gut of the infant, protecting against bacterial infections, until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies: It only borrows them.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Short-term passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In general, active immunity is long-term and can be acquired by infection followed by B cell and T cell activation, or artificially acquired by vaccines, in a process called immunization.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Historically, infectious disease has been the leading cause of death in the human population.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Over the last century, two important factors have been developed to combat their spread: sanitation and immunization.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Immunization (commonly referred to as vaccination) is the deliberate induction of an immune response, and represents the single most effective manipulation of the immune system that scientists have developed.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Immunizations are successful because they utilize the immune system's natural specificity as well as its inducibility.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The principle behind immunization is to introduce an antigen, derived from a disease-causing organism, that stimulates the immune system to develop protective immunity against that organism, but that does not itself cause the pathogenic effects of that organism.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] An antigen (short for *anti*body *gen*erator), is defined as any substance that binds to a specific antibody and elicits an adaptive immune response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Most viral vaccines are based on live attenuated viruses, whereas many bacterial vaccines are based on acellular components of microorganisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce an adaptive response, and most bacterial vaccines require the addition of *adjuvants* that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system to enhance immunogenicity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Most large molecules, including virtually all proteins and many polysaccharides, can serve as antigens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The parts of an antigen that interact with an antibody molecule or a lymphocyte receptor, are called epitopes, or antigenic determinants.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Most antigens contain a variety of epitopes and can stimulate the production of antibodies, specific T cell responses, or both.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] A very small proportion (less than 0.01%) of the total lymphocytes are able to bind to a particular antigen, which suggests that only a few cells respond to each antigen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Even in the absence of antigen stimulation, a human can produce more than 1 trillion different antibody molecules.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Millions of genes would be required to store the genetic information that produces these receptors, but, the entire human genome contains fewer than 25,000 genes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Myriad receptors are produced through a process known as clonal selection.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] According to the clonal selection theory, at birth, an animal randomly generates a vast diversity of lymphocytes (each bearing a unique antigen receptor) from information encoded in a small family of genes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] To generate each unique antigen receptor, these genes have undergone a process called V(D)J recombination, or *combinatorial diversification*, in which one gene segment recombines with other gene segments to form a single unique gene.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This assembly process generates the enormous diversity of receptors and antibodies, before the body ever encounters antigens, and enables the immune system to respond to an almost unlimited diversity of antigens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Throughout an animal's lifetime, lymphocytes that can react against the antigens an animal actually encounters are selected for action—directed against anything that expresses that antigen.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The innate and acquired portions of the immune system work together, not in spite of each other.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired arm, B, and T cells could not function without the innate system input.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] T cells are useless without antigen-presenting cells to activate them, and B cells are disabled without T cell help.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] On the other hand, the innate system would likely be overrun with pathogens without the specialized action of the adaptive immune response.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The cornerstone of the immune system is the recognition of "self" versus "non-self".
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Therefore, the mechanisms that protect the human fetus (which is considered "non-self") from attack by the immune system, are particularly interesting.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Although no comprehensive explanation has emerged to explain this mysterious, and often repeated, lack of rejection, two classical reasons may explain how the fetus is tolerated.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The first is that the fetus occupies a portion of the body protected by a non-immunological barrier, the uterus, which the immune system does not routinely patrol.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The second is that the fetus itself may promote local immunosuppression in the mother, perhaps by a process of active nutrient depletion.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] A more modern explanation for this induction of tolerance is that specific glycoproteins expressed in the uterus during pregnancy suppress the uterine immune response (see eu-FEDS).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] During pregnancy in viviparous mammals (all mammals except Monotremes), endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) are activated and produced in high quantities during the implantation of the embryo.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] They are currently known to possess immunosuppressive properties, suggesting a role in protecting the embryo from its mother's immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The immunodepressive action was the initial normal behavior of the virus, similar to HIV.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The fusion proteins were a way to spread the infection to other cells by simply merging them with the infected one (HIV does this too).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] It is believed that the ancestors of modern viviparous mammals evolved after an infection by this virus, enabling the fetus to survive the immune system of the mother.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The human genome project found several thousand ERVs classified into 24 families.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This theory, which builds on the existing clonal selection hypothesis and since 1974 has been developed mainly by Niels Jerne and Geoffrey W.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Hoffmann, is seen as being relevant to the understanding of the HIV pathogenesis and the search for an HIV vaccine.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] One of the most interesting developments in biomedical science during the past few decades has been elucidation of mechanisms mediating innate immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] One set of innate immune mechanisms is humoral, such as complement activation.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Another set comprises pattern recognition receptors such as toll-like receptors, which induce the production of interferons and other cytokines increasing resistance of cells such as monocytes to infections.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Cytokines produced during innate immune responses are among the activators of adaptive immune responses.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies exert additive or synergistic effects with mechanisms of innate immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Unstable HbS clusters Band-3, a major integral red cell protein; antibodies recognize these clusters and accelerate their removal by phagocytic cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Clustered Band 3 proteins with attached antibodies activate complement, and complement C3 fragments are opsonins recognized by the CR1 complement receptor on phagocytic cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] A population study has shown that the protective effect of the sickle-cell trait against falciparum malaria involves the augmentation of acquired as well as innate immune responses to the malaria parasite, illustrating the expected transition from innate to acquired immunity.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Repeated malaria infections strengthen acquired immunity and broaden its effects against parasites expressing different surface antigens.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] By school age most children have developed efficacious adaptive immunity against malaria.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These observations raise questions about mechanisms that favor the survival of most children in Africa while allowing some to develop potentially lethal infections.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In malaria, as in other infections, innate immune responses lead into, and stimulate, adaptive immune responses.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The genetic control of innate and acquired immunity is now a large and flourishing discipline.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Humoral and cell-mediated immune responses limit malaria parasite multiplication, and many cytokines contribute to the pathogenesis of malaria as well as to the resolution of infections.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune system evolved as an elaboration of the innate immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The amphioxus is a chordate like all vertebrates.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Its genome includes many building blocks of the adaptive immune system, but none of the true hallmarks such as somatic recombination.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] There is, however, considerable expansion in LRR genes and immunoglobulin-fold genes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] There is high polymorphism among different individuals, an example of diversity in the innate immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune system, which has been best-studied in mammals, originated in jawed fish approximately 500 million years ago.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Most of the molecules, cells, tissues, and associated mechanisms of this system of defense are found in cartilaginous fishes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Lymphocyte receptors, Ig and TCR, are found in all jawed vertebrates.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The most ancient Ig class, IgM, is membrane-bound and then secreted upon stimulation of cartilaginous fish B cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Another isotype, shark IgW, is related to mammalian IgD.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] TCRs, both α/β and γ/δ, are found in jawed fish (cladistically including mammals).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Most elements of the jawed fish system are in place thanks to the second round of whole-genome duplication (2R) that the jawed fish have undergone, providing an expanded repertoire of immune-related genes.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The immunoprotease genes involved in antigen processing and presentation as well as the class I and class II genes, are closely linked within the MHC of almost all studied species.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] These systems, along with RAG, were set in place quickly after 2R had happened.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The MHC region is paralogous to the Ig/TCR region.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Comparing paralogous regions allow for the reconstruction of a *primordial immune complex*.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The cartilaginous fish system does have one critical difference compared to the system of bony fish (including mammals): the gene segments that undergo V(D)J recombination in bony fish are not organized in huge clusters like they are in bony fish.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Instead, these parts are arranged as "miniclusters" and rearrangement by RAG is largely limited within these clusters.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] As a result, not as many combinations are available compared to bony fish.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The RAG transposon likely invaded a "UrIg2" immunoglobin gene, which had an unsplit VJ, in an ancestor of all extant jawed fish.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Splitting the V and J exons is adaptive, as it enables greater variation through changing the size of the CDR3 loop.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] This feature is inherited by all the descendants of UrIg2 such as Ig and TCR.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The jawless fish are vertebrates like the jawed fish, but belong on a different branch.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] In jawless fish, three subsets of lymphocytes use variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) for antigen binding.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The VLRs are derived from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) of the innate immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Diversity is generated by a cytosine deaminase-mediated rearrangement of LRR-based DNA segments.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] The functional dichotomy between two of the lymphocyte subsets parallels Ig and TCR molecules.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Immunity can be acquired either actively or passively.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Immunity is acquired actively when a person is exposed to foreign substances and the immune system responds.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Passive immunity is when antibodies are transferred from one host to another.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-immune-response] Both actively acquired and passively acquired immunity can be obtained by natural or artificial means.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] An **adaptive natural killer (NK) cell** or **memory-like NK cell** is a specialized natural killer cell that has the potential to form immunological memory.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] They can be distinguished from cytotoxic NK (cNK) cells by their receptor expression profile and epigenome.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Adaptive NK cells are so named for properties which they share with the adaptive immune system.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Adaptive NK cells have been identified in both humans and mice.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Persistent adaptive NK populations have been reported during viral infection, contact hypersensitivity reactions, and after stimulation by pro-inflammatory cytokines or activating receptor pathways.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] IL-12, IL-18, and IL-15 contribute to the development of adaptive NK cells by priming NK cells prior to immune stimulation.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Human adaptive NK cells in peripheral blood are likely derived from cNK cells expressing low levels of CD56, as CD56dim cNK cells are more likely to express killer-cell immunoglobulin-like receptors (KIRs) and/or CD94/NKG2C.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] These surface molecules are required for antigen sensing during infection.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Some evidence exists for tissue-resident adaptive NK cells in the liver, where a small population of CD49a+NKG2C+ NK cells has been shown to emerge in response to human cytomegalovirus infection.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] These cells differ from the predominant population of CD49a−CD49e− NK cells in the liver by their gene expression.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Signals transmitted through the IL-12 receptor combined with CD2 and MHC class I-binding receptor provide a three-prong stimulation responsible for promoting the epigenetic and phenotypic modifications that occur in association with adaptive NK cell differentiation.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] NK cells essentially "remember" the previous effects of cytokines.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] NK cells pre-activated by IL-12/15/18 transfer their enhanced IFN-γ producing capacity to daughter cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Both IL-12 and IL-18 are required for the pronounced demethylation of the CNS1 region, whereas IL-15 might serve as a survival factor.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] In addition to the IFNG gene, NKG2C+ adaptive NK cells also showed CpG demethylation of the PRDM1/BLIMP1 and ZBTB32/TZFP genes or hypermethylation of FCER1G (Fc fragment of IgE receptor Ig).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Importantly, both memory-like functionalities are antigen-unspecific and mean "remembering" a previous state of increased activation caused by cytokine exposure or stimulation via activating NK cell receptors.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Unique and expanded adaptive NK cell populations were observed in peripheral blood in humans that have been previously infected with Human Cytomegalovirus (HCMV).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] These NK cells bear activating MHC class I-binding receptors, typically CD94/NKG2C, demonstrate reduced activation and degranulation in response to activated autologous T cells and they are CD56dim CD16+.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] In comparison to CD56dim cNK cells, adaptive NK cells generally show decreased expression of surface CD7, CD161, NKp30, NKp46, and SIGLEC-7 but demonstrate retained or even higher expression of CD2, CD57, and CD85j (ILT2, LILRB1).
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] None of these surface marker expression patterns are inherently specific for adaptive NK cells, but together they may help to identify discrete populations of adaptive NK cells.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Human adaptive NK cells have the hypomethylated region of IFN-γ promoter.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] After stimulation through CD16 ligation adaptive NK cells produce large amounts of IFN-γ and also extensively proliferate.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] The cytotoxicity of adaptive NK cells remains a constant question in this field.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] It had been indicated similar or reduced degranulation of CD107a as compared to cNK cells after CD16 ligation or stimulation with antibody-coated tumor targets.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] The discovery of memory in the human NK compartment makes us wonder whether it could be harnessed by vaccination.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] This could be particularly effective in HIV infections where CD4+T cells get rapidly depleted as it provides an alternative where B and T cells cannot be harnessed.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] The clinical application of NK cells with memory-like properties can significantly increase the efficiency of these cells and pave the way for the new NK cell-based clinical approaches for the cancer treatment.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Adaptive NK cells can mediate the enhanced antitumor effects, that may be due to their increased cytotoxicity, high IFN-γ production capacity, and persistence in large numbers in the host.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Clinical use of allogeneic NK cells is promising for the treatment of leukemia.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] KIR-ligand mismatch has a beneficial effect on the alloreactivity of donor NK cells against recipient leukemia.
[src:t-cell/adaptive-nk-cells] Besides, it has been shown that the adoptive transfer of alloreactive NK cells does not cause graft-versus-host disease (GVHD), but instead suppresses GVHD.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] In immunology, **affinity maturation** is the process by which TFH cell-activated B cells produce antibodies with increased affinity for antigen during the course of an immune response.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] With repeated exposures to the same antigen, a host will produce antibodies of successively greater affinities.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] A secondary response can elicit antibodies with several fold greater affinity than in a primary response.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Affinity maturation primarily occurs on membrane immunoglobulin of germinal center B cells and as a direct result of somatic hypermutation (SHM) and selection by TFH cells.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Clonal selection: B cells that have undergone SHM must compete for limiting growth resources, including the availability of antigen and paracrine signals from TFH cells.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] The follicular dendritic cells (FDCs) of the germinal centers present antigen to the B cells, and the B cell progeny with the highest affinities for antigen, having gained a competitive advantage, are favored for positive selection leading to their survival.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Positive selection is based on steady cross-talk between TFH cells and their cognate antigen presenting GC B cell.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Because a limited number of TFH cells reside in the germinal center, only highly competitive B cells stably conjugate with TFH cells and thus receive T cell-dependent survival signals.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] B cell progeny that have undergone SHM, but bind antigen with lower affinity will be out-competed, and be deleted.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Over several rounds of selection, the resultant secreted antibodies produced will have effectively increased affinities for antigen.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Like the natural prototype, the *in vitro* affinity maturation is based on the principles of mutation and selection.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] The *in vitro* affinity maturation has successfully been used to optimize antibodies, antibody fragments or other peptide molecules like antibody mimetics.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Random mutations inside the CDRs are introduced using radiation, chemical mutagens or error-prone PCR.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] In addition, the genetic diversity can be increased by chain shuffling.
[src:t-cell/affinity-maturation] Two or three rounds of mutation and selection using display methods like phage display usually results in antibody fragments with affinities in the low nanomolar range.
[src:t-cell/allergen] An **allergen** is an otherwise harmless substance that triggers an allergic reaction in sensitive individuals by stimulating an immune response.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In technical terms, an allergen is an antigen that is capable of stimulating a type-I hypersensitivity reaction in atopic individuals through immunoglobulin E (IgE) responses.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Most humans mount significant immunoglobulin E responses only as a defense against parasitic infections.
[src:t-cell/allergen] However, some individuals may respond to many common environmental antigens.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In atopic individuals, non-parasitic antigens stimulate inappropriate IgE production, leading to type I hypersensitivity.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Sensitivities vary widely from one person (or from one animal) to another.
[src:t-cell/allergen] A very broad range of substances can be allergens to sensitive individuals.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The World Health Organization and International Union of Immunological Societies (WHO/IUIS) Allergen Nomenclature Sub-Committee maintains a webpage listing every protein (as well as some carbohydrates) that have elicited a confirmed IgE reaction in humans.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Allergens can be found in a variety of sources, such as dust mite excretion, Food allergies are not as common as food sensitivity, but some foods such as peanuts (a legume), nuts, seafood and shellfish are the cause of serious allergies in many people.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The United States Food and Drug Administration recognizes nine foods as major food allergens: organic fats as well as sulfites (chemical-based, often found in flavors and colors in foods) at 10ppm and over.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In other countries, due to differences in the genetic profiles of their citizens and different levels of exposure to specific foods, the official allergen lists will vary.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Canada recognizes all nine of the allergens recognized by the US as well as mustard.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The European Union additionally recognizes other organic grains .
[src:t-cell/allergen] An allergic reaction can be caused by any form of direct contact with the allergen—consuming food or drink one is sensitive to (ingestion), breathing in pollen, perfume or pet dander (inhalation), or brushing a body part against an allergy-causing plant (direct contact).
[src:t-cell/allergen] Other common causes of serious allergy are wasp, fire ant and bee stings, penicillin, and latex.
[src:t-cell/allergen] An extremely serious form of an allergic reaction is called anaphylaxis.
[src:t-cell/allergen] One form of treatment is the administration of sterile epinephrine to the person experiencing anaphylaxis, which suppresses the body's overreaction to the allergen, and allows for the patient to be transported to a medical facility.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Substances that cause a non-IgE-mediated, non-type-I hypersensitivity reaction are also called "allergens" in a broad sense.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In general, all contact dermatitides are type IV reactions, despite the name "allergic contact dermatitis".
[src:t-cell/allergen] Various trees and wood products such as paper, cardboard, MDF etc. can also cause mild to severe allergy symptoms through touch or inhalation of sawdust such as asthma and skin rash.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Seasonal allergy symptoms are commonly experienced during specific parts of the year, usually during spring, summer or fall when certain trees or grasses pollinate.
[src:t-cell/allergen] This depends on the kind of tree or grass.
[src:t-cell/allergen] For instance, some trees such as oak, elm, and maple pollinate in the spring, while grasses such as Bermuda, timothy and orchard pollinate in the summer.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Grass allergy is generally linked to hay fever because their symptoms and causes are somehow similar to each other.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Symptoms include rhinitis, which causes sneezing and a runny nose, as well as allergic conjunctivitis, which includes watering and itchy eyes.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Also an initial tickle on the roof of the mouth or in the back of the throat may be experienced.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Also, depending on the season, the symptoms may be more severe and people may experience coughing, wheezing, and irritability.
[src:t-cell/allergen] A few people even become depressed, lose their appetite, or have problems sleeping.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Moreover, since the sinuses may also become congested, some people experience headaches.
[src:t-cell/allergen] If both parents have had allergies in the past, there is a 66% chance for the individual to experience seasonal allergies, and the risk lowers to 60% if just one parent has had allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The immune system also has strong influence on seasonal allergies, because it reacts differently to diverse allergens like pollen.
[src:t-cell/allergen] When an allergen enters the body of an individual that is predisposed to allergies, it triggers an immune reaction and the production of antibodies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] These allergen antibodies migrate to mast cells lining the nose, eyes, and lungs.
[src:t-cell/allergen] When an allergen drifts into the nose more than once, mast cells release a slew of chemicals or histamines that irritate and inflame the moist membranes lining the nose and produce the symptoms of an allergic reaction: scratchy throat, itching, sneezing and watery eyes.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Among seasonal allergies, there are some allergens that fuse together and produce a new type of allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergen] For instance, grass pollen allergens cross-react with food allergy proteins in vegetables such as onion, lettuce, carrots, celery, and corn.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Besides, the cousins of birch pollen allergens, like apples, grapes, peaches, celery, and apricots, produce severe itching in the ears and throat.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The cypress pollen allergy brings a cross reactivity between diverse species like olive, privet, ash and Russian olive tree pollen allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In some rural areas, there is another form of seasonal grass allergy, combining airborne particles of pollen mixed with mold.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Recent research has suggested that humans might develop allergies as a defense to fight off parasites.
[src:t-cell/allergen] According to Yale University Immunologist Ruslan Medzhitov, protease allergens cleave the same sensor proteins that evolved to detect proteases produced by the parasitic worms.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Additionally, a new report on seasonal allergies called "Extreme allergies and Global Warming", have found that many allergy triggers are worsening due to climate change.
[src:t-cell/allergen] 16 states in the United States were named as "Allergen Hotspots" for large increases in allergenic tree pollen if global warming pollution keeps increasing.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Therefore, researchers on this report claimed that global warming is bad news for millions of asthmatics in the United States whose asthma attacks are triggered by seasonal allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Seasonal allergies are one of the main triggers for asthma, along with colds or flu, cigarette smoke and exercise.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In Canada, for example, up to 75% of asthmatics also have seasonal allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Based on the symptoms seen on the patient, the answers given in terms of symptom evaluation and a physical exam, doctors can make a diagnosis to identify if the patient has a seasonal allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergen] After performing the diagnosis, the doctor is able to tell the main cause of the allergic reaction and recommend the treatment to follow.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Two tests have to be done in order to determine the cause: a blood test and a skin test.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Allergists do skin tests in one of two ways: either dropping some purified liquid of the allergen onto the skin and pricking the area with a small needle; or injecting a small amount of allergen under the skin.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Alternative tools are available to identify seasonal allergies, such as laboratory tests, imaging tests, and nasal endoscopy.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In the laboratory tests, the doctor will take a nasal smear and it will be examined microscopically for factors that may indicate a cause: increased numbers of eosinophils (white blood cells), which indicates an allergic condition.
[src:t-cell/allergen] If there is a high count of eosinophils, an allergic condition might be present.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Another laboratory test is the blood test for IgE (immunoglobulin production), such as the radioallergosorbent test (RAST) or the more recent enzyme allergosorbent tests (EAST), implemented to detect high levels of allergen-specific IgE in response to particular allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Although blood tests are less accurate than the skin tests, they can be performed on patients unable to undergo skin testing.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Imaging tests can be useful to detect sinusitis in people who have chronic rhinitis, and they can work when other test results are ambiguous.
[src:t-cell/allergen] There is also nasal endoscopy, wherein a tube is inserted through the nose with a small camera to view the passageways and examine any irregularities in the nose structure.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Endoscopy can be used for some cases of chronic or unresponsive seasonal rhinitis.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In 1952 basidiospores were described as being possible airborne allergens and were linked to asthma in 1969.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Basidiospores are the dominant airborne fungal allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Fungal allergies are associated with seasonal asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergen] They are considered to be a major source of airborne allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The basidiospore family include mushrooms, rusts, smuts, brackets, and puffballs.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The airborne spores from mushrooms reach levels comparable to those of mold and pollens.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The levels of mushroom respiratory allergy are as high as 30% of those with allergic disorder, but it is believed to be less than 1% of food allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Heavy rainfall (which increases fungal spore release) is associated with increased hospital admissions of children with asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergen] A study in New Zealand found that 22 percent of patients with respiratory allergic disorders tested positive for basidiospores allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Mushroom spore allergies can cause either immediate allergic symptomatology or delayed allergic reactions.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Those with asthma are more likely to have immediate allergic reactions and those with allergic rhinitis are more likely to have delayed allergic responses.
[src:t-cell/allergen] A study found that 27% of patients were allergic to basidiomycete mycelia extracts and 32% were allergic to basidiospore extracts, thus demonstrating the high incidence of fungal sensitisation in individuals with suspected allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] It has been found that out of basidiomycete caps, mycelia, and spore extracts, the spore extracts are the most reliable extract for diagnosing basidiomycete allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In Canada, 8% of children attending allergy clinics were found to be allergic to *Ganoderma*, a basidiospore.
[src:t-cell/allergen] *Pleurotus ostreatus*, *Cladosporium*, and *Calvatia cyathiformis* are significant airborne spores.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Other significant fungal allergens include *Aspergillus* and *Alternaria*-*Penicillium* families.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In India, *Fomes pectinatus* is a predominant air-borne allergen affecting up to 22% of patients with respiratory allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Some fungal air-borne allergens such as *Coprinus comatus* are associated with worsening of eczematous skin lesions.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Children who are born during Autumn months (during fungal spore season) are more likely to develop asthmatic symptoms later in life.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Treatment includes over-the-counter medications, antihistamines, nasal decongestants, allergy shots, and alternative medicine.
[src:t-cell/allergen] In the case of nasal symptoms, antihistamines are normally the first option.
[src:t-cell/allergen] They may be taken together with pseudoephedrine to help relieve a stuffy nose and they can stop the itching and sneezing.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Over-the-counter options include clemastine.
[src:t-cell/allergen] However, these antihistamines may cause extreme drowsiness, therefore, people are advised to not operate heavy machinery or drive while taking this kind of medication.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Other side effects include dry mouth, blurred vision, constipation, difficulty with urination, confusion, and lightheadedness.
[src:t-cell/allergen] There is also a newer second generation of antihistamines that are generally classified as non-sedating antihistamines or anti-drowsy, which include cetirizine, loratadine, and fexofenadine.
[src:t-cell/allergen] An example of nasal decongestants is pseudoephedrine and its side-effects include insomnia, restlessness, and difficulty urinating.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Some other nasal sprays are available by prescription, including azelastine and ipratropium bromide.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Some of their side-effects include drowsiness.
[src:t-cell/allergen] For eye symptoms, it is important to first bathe the eyes with plain eyewash to reduce irritation.
[src:t-cell/allergen] People should not wear contact lenses during episodes of conjunctivitis.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Allergen immunotherapy treatment involves administering doses of allergens to accustom the body to induce specific long-term tolerance.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Allergy immunotherapy can be administered orally (as sublingual tablets or sublingual drops), or by injections under the skin (subcutaneous).
[src:t-cell/allergen] Immunotherapy contains a small amount of the substance that triggers the allergic reactions.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Gradual introduction is also used for egg and milk allergies as a home-based therapy mainly for children.
[src:t-cell/allergen] Such methods cited in the UK involve the gradual introduction of the allergen in a cooked form where the protein allergenicity has been reduced to become less potent.
[src:t-cell/allergen] By reintroducing the allergen from a fully cooked, usually baked, state, research suggests that a tolerance can emerge to certain egg and milk allergies under the supervision of a dietitian or specialist.
[src:t-cell/allergen] The suitability of this treatment is debated between British and North American experts.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] An **allergy** is an exaggerated immune response where the body mistakenly identifies an ordinarily harmless allergen as a threat.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic reactions give rise to **allergic diseases** such as hay fever, allergic conjunctivitis, allergic asthma, atopic dermatitis, food allergies, and anaphylaxis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Symptoms of allergic diseases may include red eyes, an itchy rash, sneezing, coughing, a runny nose, shortness of breath, or swelling.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Common allergens include pollen, certain foods, metals, insect stings, medications, and materials, such as latex.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The development of allergies is due to genetic and environmental factors.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The mechanism of allergic reactions involves immunoglobulin E antibodies (IgE) binding to an allergen and then to a receptor on mast cells or basophils, where they trigger the release of inflammatory chemicals such as histamine.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Diagnosis is typically based on a person's medical history.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Further testing of the skin or blood may be useful in certain cases.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Positive tests, however, may not necessarily mean there is a significant allergy to the substance in question.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Early exposure of children to potential allergens may be protective.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Treatments for allergies include avoidance of known allergens and the use of medications such as steroids and antihistamines.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In severe reactions, injectable adrenaline (epinephrine) is recommended.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy, which gradually exposes people to larger and larger amounts of allergen, is useful for some types of allergies such as hay fever and reactions to insect bites.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In the developed world, about 20% of people are affected by allergic rhinitis, food allergy affects 10% of adults and 8% of children, and about 20% have or have had atopic dermatitis at some point in time.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Depending on the country, about 1–18% of people have asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Anaphylaxis occurs in between 0.05–2% of people.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Rates of many allergic diseases appear to be increasing.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The word "allergy" was first used by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Many allergens, such as dust or pollen, are airborne particles.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In these cases, symptoms arise in areas exposed to air, such as the eyes, nose, and lungs.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] For instance, allergic rhinitis, also known as hay fever, irritates the nose, sneezing, itching, and redness of the eyes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Inhaled allergens can also lead to increased production of mucus in the lungs, shortness of breath, coughing, and wheezing.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic rhinitis can simultaneously occur with other allergic responses such as asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Aside from these ambient allergens, allergic reactions can result from foods, insect stings, and reactions to medications like aspirin and antibiotics such as penicillin.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Symptoms of food allergy include abdominal pain, bloating, vomiting, diarrhea, itchy skin, and hives.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Food allergies rarely cause respiratory (asthmatic) reactions, or rhinitis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Insect stings, food, antibiotics, and certain medicines may produce a systemic allergic response that is also called anaphylaxis; multiple organ systems can be affected, including the digestive system, the respiratory system, and the circulatory system.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Depending on the severity, anaphylaxis can include skin reactions, bronchoconstriction, swelling, low blood pressure, coma, and death.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This type of reaction can be triggered suddenly or have a delayed onset.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The anaphylactic reaction may seem to subside, but may recur over time.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Substances that come into contact with the skin, such as latex, are also common causes of allergic reactions, known as contact dermatitis or eczema.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Skin allergies frequently cause rashes, or swelling and inflammation within the skin, in what is known as a "wheal and flare" reaction characteristic of hives and angioedema.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] With insect stings, a large local reaction may occur as an area of skin redness greater than 10 cm in size that can last one to two days.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This reaction may also occur after immunotherapy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The skin forms an effective barrier to the entry of most allergens, but this barrier cannot withstand everything.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] For example, an insect sting can breach the barrier and inject allergen into the affected spot.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] When an allergen enters the epidermis or dermis, it triggers a localized allergic reaction which activates the mast cells in the skin resulting in an immediate increase in permeability of blood vessels, leading to fluid leakage and swelling in the affected area.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Mast-cell activation also stimulates a skin lesion called the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Then the release of chemicals from local nerve endings by a nerve axon reflex causes the widening of surrounding cutaneous blood vessels, which causes redness of the surrounding skin.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] As part of the allergic response, the body has developed a secondary response that, in some individuals, causes a more widespread and sustained skin swelling.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This usually occurs about 8 hours after the allergen originally comes in contact with the skin.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] When an allergen is ingested, a dispersed form of wheal-and-flare reaction, known as urticaria or hives, will appear when the allergen enters the bloodstream and eventually reaches the skin.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This same skin reactivity allows allergists to test for existing allergies by injecting a small amount of an allergen into the skin, which causes a reaction at the injection site.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Even though these injections are very small and local, they still pose the risk of causing systemic anaphylaxis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Substances that come into contact with the airways may trigger allergic reactions in the nose, sinuses, throat and lungs.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic rhinitis, often referred to as hay fever, is one of the most common airway allergies and is characterized by sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching of the nose and eyes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Airborne allergens commonly associated with allergic rhinitis include pollen, house dust mites, animal dander and mold spores.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic reactions involving the lower airways may contribute to allergic asthma, in which exposure to allergens can lead to bronchoconstriction, wheezing, coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, animal allergens and occupational exposures such as flour dust or chemical sensitizers.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some allergic airway reactions may occur rapidly after exposure, while others develop over several hours.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Severe reactions involving airway swelling may impair breathing and constitute a medical emergency.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) is responsible for distinguishing pathogenic organisms from harmless food proteins and commensal bacteria.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Antigens sampled across the intestinal epithelium are presented by CD103+ dendritic cells, which migrate to mesenteric lymph nodes and promote differentiation of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells (Tregs).
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] These Tregs subsequently return to the intestinal lamina propria, where cytokines such as interleukin-10 and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) contribute to the maintenance of immune tolerance and suppression of allergic T helper 2 (Th2) responses.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Disruption of these regulatory pathways may contribute to allergic sensitization and the development of food allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Impairment of the intestinal epithelial barrier, altered antigen processing, inflammation, or reduced regulatory T-cell activity may shift immune responses toward IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Such defects in oral tolerance have been associated with increased Th2 polarization, elevated allergen-specific IgE production, and reduced regulatory immune activity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Environmental and dietary factors, including vitamin D deficiency, infections, antibiotic exposure, and changes in food processing, may also influence allergy development through their effects on gut immunity and epithelial integrity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The intestinal microbiome is increasingly recognized as an important factor in allergy development.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Early-life alterations in the composition and diversity of the intestinal microbiota have been associated with an increased risk of food allergy and atopic disease.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Commensal bacteria contribute to immune maturation, maintenance of epithelial barrier function, and induction of tolerogenic immune responses.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Reduced microbial diversity and loss of certain bacterial taxa may impair oral tolerance and promote allergic sensitization.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Short-chain fatty acids produced by intestinal bacteria may further support regulatory immune pathways and intestinal barrier integrity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Sensitization to food allergens may also occur through non-oral routes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Exposure to allergens through damaged skin, particularly in individuals with impaired skin barriers such as those with atopic dermatitis, may predispose to food allergy if oral tolerance has not yet been established.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This has contributed to the hypothesis that the timing, route, and context of allergen exposure influence whether tolerance or allergic sensitization develops.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Research into gastrointestinal immune mechanisms has influenced preventive approaches to food allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts and eggs, during infancy has been associated in some populations with a reduced risk of food allergy, likely by promoting oral tolerance during critical periods of immune development.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Risk factors for allergies can be placed in two broad categories: host and environmental factors.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Host factors include heredity, sex, race, and age, with heredity being by far the most significant.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] However, there has been a recent increase in the incidence of allergic disorders that cannot be explained by genetic factors alone.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Four major environmental candidates are alterations in exposure to infectious diseases during early childhood, environmental pollution, allergen levels, and dietary changes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Dust mite allergy, also known as house dust allergy, is a sensitization and allergic reaction to the droppings of house dust mites.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The allergy is common and can trigger allergic reactions such as asthma, eczema, or itching.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The mite's gut contains potent digestive enzymes (notably peptidase 1) that persist in their faeces and are major inducers of allergic reactions such as wheezing.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The mite's exoskeleton can also contribute to allergic reactions.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Unlike scabies mites or skin follicle mites, house dust mites do not burrow under the skin and are not parasitic.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Dust mite-proof encasements to mattress, pillow, and duvet prevent chronic contact with allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A wide variety of foods can cause allergic reactions, but 90% of allergic responses to foods are caused by cow's milk, soy, eggs, wheat, peanuts, tree nuts, fish, and shellfish.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Other food allergies, affecting less than 1 person per 10,000 population, may be considered "rare".
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The most common food allergy in the US population is a sensitivity to crustacea.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Although peanut allergies are notorious for their severity, peanut allergies are not the most common food allergy in adults or children.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Other allergens may trigger severe or life-threatening reactions and are more common when combined with asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Rates of allergies differ between adults and children.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Children can sometimes outgrow peanut allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Egg allergies affect one to two percent of children but are outgrown by about two-thirds of children by the age of 5.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The sensitivity is usually to proteins in the white, rather than the yolk.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Milk-protein allergies—distinct from lactose intolerance—are most common in children.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Approximately 60% of milk-protein reactions are immunoglobulin E–mediated, with the remaining usually attributable to inflammation of the colon.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some people are unable to tolerate milk from goats or sheep as well as from cows, and many are also unable to tolerate dairy products such as cheese.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Roughly 10% of children with a milk allergy will have a reaction to beef.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Lactose intolerance, a common reaction to milk, is not a form of allergy at all, but due to the absence of an enzyme in the digestive tract.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Those with tree nut allergies may be allergic to one or many tree nuts, including pecans, pistachios, and walnuts.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In addition, seeds, including sesame seeds and poppy seeds, contain oils in which protein is present, which may elicit an allergic reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergens can be transferred from one food to another through genetic engineering; however, genetic modification can also remove allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Little research has been done on the natural variation of allergen concentrations in unmodified crops.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Latex can trigger an IgE-mediated cutaneous, respiratory, and systemic reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The prevalence of latex allergy in the general population is believed to be less than one percent.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In a hospital study, 1 in 800 surgical patients (0.125 percent) reported latex sensitivity, although the sensitivity among healthcare workers is higher, between seven and ten percent.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Researchers attribute this higher level to the exposure of healthcare workers to areas with significant airborne latex allergens, such as operating rooms, intensive-care units, and dental suites.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] These latex-rich environments may sensitize healthcare workers who regularly inhale allergenic proteins.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The most prevalent response to latex is allergic contact dermatitis, a delayed hypersensitivity reaction that manifests as dry, crusted lesions.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This reaction usually lasts 48–96 hours.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Sweating or rubbing the area under the glove aggravates the lesions, possibly leading to ulcerations.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Anaphylactic reactions occur most often in sensitive patients who have been exposed to a surgeon's latex gloves during abdominal surgery, but other mucosal exposures, such as dental procedures, can also produce systemic reactions.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Latex and banana sensitivity may cross-react.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Furthermore, those with latex allergy may also have sensitivities to avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] These people often have perioral itching and local urticaria.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Only occasionally have these food-induced allergies induced systemic responses.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Researchers suspect that the cross-reactivity of latex with banana, avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut occurs because latex proteins are structurally homologous with some other plant proteins.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] About 10% of people report that they are allergic to penicillin; however, of that 10%, 90% turn out not to be.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Serious allergies only occur in about 0.03%.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] One of the main sources of human allergies is insects.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Insect bites, stings, ingestion, and inhalation can trigger an insect allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Another non-food protein reaction, urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, originates after contact with poison ivy, eastern poison oak, western poison oak, or poison sumac.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Urushiol, which is not itself a protein, acts as a hapten and chemically reacts with, binds to, and changes the shape of integral membrane proteins on exposed skin cells.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The immune system does not recognize the affected cells as normal parts of the body, causing a T-cell-mediated immune response.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Of these poisonous plants, sumac is the most virulent.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The resulting dermatological response to the reaction between urushiol and membrane proteins includes redness, swelling, papules, vesicles, blisters, and streaking.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Estimates vary on the fraction of the population that will have an immune system response.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Approximately 25% of the population will have a strong allergic response to urushiol.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In general, approximately 80–90% of adults will develop a rash if they are exposed to 0.0050 mg (7.7×10−5 gr) of purified urushiol.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some people are so sensitive that a molecular trace on the skin can initiate an allergic reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are strongly familial; identical twins are likely to have the same allergic diseases about 70% of the time; the same allergy occurs about 40% of the time in non-identical twins.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic parents are more likely to have allergic children and those children's allergies are likely to be more severe than those in children of non-allergic parents.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some allergies, however, are not consistent along genealogies; parents who are allergic to peanuts may have children who are allergic to ragweed.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The likelihood of developing allergies is inherited and related to an irregularity in the immune system, but the specific allergen is not.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The risk of allergic sensitization and the development of allergies varies with age, with young children most at risk.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Several studies have shown that IgE levels are highest in childhood and fall rapidly between the ages of 10 and 30 years.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The peak prevalence of hay fever is highest in children and young adults, and the incidence of asthma is highest in children under 10.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Ethnicity may play a role in some allergies; however, racial factors have been difficult to separate from environmental influences and changes due to migration.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It has been suggested that different genetic loci are responsible for asthma, to be specific, in people of European, Hispanic, Asian, and African origins.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some loci, such as PRDM2 and POU2AF1, showed pleiotropic effects linking allergic and autoimmune conditions, suggesting shared inflammatory pathways across epithelial tissues.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Within atopic airway disease specifically, the same review noted that IL-13—produced mainly by activated TH2 cells—is a key driver of eosinophilic airway inflammation and remodeling, acting partly through pathways independent of IgE and eosinophils.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are caused by inappropriate immunological responses to harmless antigens driven by a TH2-mediated immune response.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Many bacteria and viruses elicit a TH1-mediated immune response, which down-regulates TH2 responses.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The first proposed mechanism of action of the hygiene hypothesis was that insufficient stimulation of the TH1 arm of the immune system leads to an overactive TH2 arm, which in turn leads to allergic disease.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In other words, individuals living in too sterile an environment are not exposed to enough pathogens to keep the immune system busy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Since our bodies evolved to deal with a certain level of such pathogens, when they are not exposed to this level, the immune system will attack harmless antigens.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Thus, normally benign microbial objects—like pollen—will trigger an immune response.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It is used to explain the increase in allergic diseases that have been seen since industrialization, and the higher incidence of allergic diseases in more developed countries.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The hygiene hypothesis has now expanded to include exposure to symbiotic bacteria and parasites as important modulators of immune system development, along with infectious agents.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Epidemiological data support the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Longitudinal studies in the third world demonstrate an increase in immunological disorders as a country grows more affluent and, it is presumed, cleaner.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The use of antibiotics in the first year of life has been linked to asthma and other allergic diseases.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The use of antibacterial cleaning products has also been associated with a higher incidence of asthma, as has birth by caesarean section rather than vaginal birth.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Chronic stress can aggravate allergic conditions.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This has been attributed to a T helper 2 (TH2)-predominant response driven by suppression of interleukin 12 by both the autonomic nervous system and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Stress management in highly susceptible individuals may improve symptoms.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are more common in industrialized countries than in countries that are more traditional or agricultural, and there is a higher rate of allergic disease in urban populations versus rural populations, although these differences are becoming less defined.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Historically, the trees planted in urban areas were predominantly male to prevent litter from seeds and fruits, but the high ratio of male trees causes high pollen counts, a phenomenon that horticulturist Tom Ogren has called "botanical sexism".
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Alterations in exposure to microorganisms is another plausible explanation, at present, for the increase in atopic allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Endotoxin exposure reduces release of inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α, IFNγ, interleukin-10, and interleukin-12 from white blood cells (leukocytes) that circulate in the blood.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Certain microbe-sensing proteins, known as Toll-like receptors, found on the surface of cells in the body, are also thought to be involved in these processes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Parasitic worms and similar parasites are present in untreated drinking water in developing countries, and were present in the water of developed countries until the routine chlorination and purification of drinking water supplies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Recent research has shown that some common parasites, such as intestinal worms (e.g., hookworms), secrete chemicals into the gut wall (and, hence, the bloodstream) that suppress the immune system and prevent the body from attacking the parasite.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This gives rise to a new slant on the hygiene hypothesis theory—that co-evolution of humans and parasites has led to an immune system that functions correctly only in the presence of the parasites.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Without them, the immune system becomes unbalanced and oversensitive.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In particular, research suggests that allergies may coincide with the delayed establishment of gut flora in infants.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] However, the research to support this theory is conflicting, with some studies performed in China and Ethiopia showing an increase in allergy in people infected with intestinal worms.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Clinical trials have been initiated to test the effectiveness of helminthic therapy with certain worms in treating some allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It may be that the term 'parasite' could turn out to be inappropriate, and in fact a hitherto unsuspected symbiosis is at work.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] These TH2 cells interact with other lymphocytes called B cells, whose role is the production of antibodies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Coupled with signals provided by IL-4, this interaction stimulates the B cell to begin production of a large amount of a particular type of antibody known as IgE.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Secreted IgE circulates in the blood and binds to an IgE-specific receptor (a kind of Fc receptor called FcεRI) on the surface of other kinds of immune cells called mast cells and basophils, which are both involved in the acute inflammatory response.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] At this stage, the IgE-coated cells are sensitized to the allergen.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] If later exposure to the same allergen occurs, the allergen can bind to IgE molecules held on the surface of the mast cells or basophils.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Cross-linking of the IgE and Fc receptors occurs when more than one IgE-receptor complex interacts with the same allergenic molecule and activates the sensitized cell.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This results in rhinorrhea, itchiness, dyspnea, and anaphylaxis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Depending on the individual, allergen, and mode of introduction, the symptoms can be system-wide (classical anaphylaxis) or localized to specific body systems.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Asthma is localized to the respiratory system, and eczema is localized to the dermis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] After the chemical mediators of the acute response subside, late-phase responses can often occur.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This is due to the migration of other leukocytes such as neutrophils, lymphocytes, eosinophils, and macrophages to the initial site.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The reaction is usually seen 2–24 hours after the original reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Cytokines from mast cells may play a role in the persistence of long-term effects.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Late-phase responses in asthma differ slightly from those seen in other allergic responses.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] They are still caused by the release of mediators from eosinophils and remain dependent on TH2 cell activity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Although allergic contact dermatitis is termed an "allergic" reaction (which usually refers to type I hypersensitivity), its pathophysiology involves a reaction that more correctly corresponds to a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In type IV hypersensitivity, there is activation of certain types of T cells (CD8+) that destroy target cells on contact, as well as activated macrophages that produce hydrolytic enzymes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Effective management of allergic diseases relies on the ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergy testing can help confirm or rule out allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Correct diagnosis, counseling, and avoidance advice based on valid allergy test results reduce the incidence of symptoms and need for medications, and improve quality of life.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] To assess the presence of allergen-specific IgE antibodies, two different methods can be used: a skin prick test or an allergy blood test.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Both methods are recommended, and they have similar diagnostic value.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Skin prick tests and blood tests are equally cost-effective, and health economic evidence shows that both tests are cost-effective compared with no test.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Early and more accurate diagnoses save costs due to reduced consultations, referrals to secondary care, misdiagnosis, and emergency admissions.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergy undergoes dynamic changes over time.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Regular allergy testing of relevant allergens provides information on if and how patient management can be changed to improve health and quality of life.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Annual testing is often the practice for determining whether allergy to milk, egg, soy, and wheat have been outgrown, and the testing interval is extended to 2–3 years for allergy to peanut, tree nuts, fish, and crustacean shellfish.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Results of follow-up testing can guide decision-making regarding whether and when it is safe to introduce or re-introduce allergenic food into the diet.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Skin testing is also known as "puncture testing" and "prick testing" since it involves a series of tiny punctures or pricks being placed into the patient's skin.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Tiny amounts of suspected allergens and/or their extracts (*e.g.*, pollen, grass, mite proteins, peanut extract) are introduced to sites on the skin marked with pen or dye (the ink/dye should be carefully selected, lest it cause an allergic response itself).
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A negative and positive control are also included for comparison (e.g., negative is saline or glycerin; positive is histamine).
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A small plastic or metal device is used to puncture or prick the skin.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Sometimes, allergens are injected "intradermally" into the patient's skin, with a needle and syringe.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Common areas for testing include the inside of the forearm and the back.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] If the patient is allergic to the substance, then a visible inflammatory reaction will usually occur within 30 minutes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] This response ranges from slight reddening of the skin to a full-blown hive (called "wheal and flare") in more sensitive patients, similar to a mosquito bite.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Interpretation of the results of the skin prick test is usually done by allergists on a severity scale, with +/− meaning borderline reactivity, and 4+ representing a large reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Increasingly, allergists are measuring and recording the diameter of the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Interpretation by well-trained allergists is often guided by relevant literature.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In general, a positive response is interpreted when the wheal of an antigen is ≥3 mm larger than the wheal of the negative control (e.g., saline or glycerin).
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some patients may believe they have determined their own allergic sensitivity from observation.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A skin test is much better than patient observation for allergy detection.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] If a serious life-threatening anaphylactic reaction has brought a patient in for evaluation, some allergists may prefer to perform an initial blood test before conducting a skin prick test.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Skin testing may also not be possible in patients with widespread skin disease or those who have taken antihistamine within the past several days.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Patch testing is a diagnostic method used to identify substances that cause allergic contact dermatitis through a delayed hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] During the procedure, small amounts of potential allergens are applied to the skin, usually on the back, using adhesive patches containing standardized allergen preparations.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The patches are typically left in place for 48 hours, after which the skin is examined for localized eczematous reactions.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Additional readings are commonly performed 72–96 hours after application because allergic contact reactions may develop slowly.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Unlike skin prick testing, which is used to diagnose immediate IgE-mediated allergies, patch testing evaluates delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions mediated by T cells.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergy blood testing, typically measuring allergen-specific IgE, is a quick test that can be ordered by a qualified healthcare professional.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Unlike skin-prick testing, it is not affected by antihistamines and may be used when skin testing is impractical, such as in people with extensive eczema or other skin disease, in pregnancy, or when there is concern about provoking symptoms.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It can be performed in adults and children, including infants, although results must be interpreted together with the clinical history because sensitisation does not always mean clinical allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] An allergy blood test is available through most laboratories.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A sample of the patient's blood is sent to a laboratory for analysis, and the results are sent back a few days later.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Multiple allergens can be detected with a single blood sample.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergy blood tests are very safe because the person is not exposed to any allergens during the testing procedure.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] After the onset of anaphylaxis or a severe allergic reaction, guidelines recommend that emergency departments obtain a time-sensitive blood test to measure tryptase levels and assess for mast cells activation.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The test measures the concentration of specific IgE antibodies in the blood.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Quantitative IgE test results increase the possibility of ranking how different substances may affect symptoms.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A rule of thumb is that the higher the IgE antibody value, the greater the likelihood of symptoms.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergens found at low levels that today do not result in symptoms cannot predict future symptom development.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The quantitative allergy blood result can help determine what a patient is allergic to, predict and monitor disease progression, estimate the risk of a severe reaction, and explain cross-reactivity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A low total IgE level is not adequate to rule out sensitization to commonly inhaled allergens.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Statistical methods, such as ROC curves, predictive value calculations, and likelihood ratios have been used to examine the relationship of various testing methods to each other.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] These methods have shown that patients with high total IgE have a high probability of allergic sensitization, but further investigation with allergy tests for specific IgE antibodies for a carefully chosen set of allergens is often warranted.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Laboratory methods to measure specific IgE antibodies for allergy testing include enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, radioallergosorbent test, fluorescent enzyme immunoassay, and chemiluminescence immunoassay.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Before a diagnosis of allergic disease can be confirmed, other plausible causes of the presenting symptoms must be considered.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Vasomotor rhinitis, for example, is one of many illnesses that share symptoms with allergic rhinitis, underscoring the need for professional differential diagnosis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Once a diagnosis of asthma, rhinitis, anaphylaxis, or other allergic disease has been made, there are several methods for discovering the causative agent of that allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Giving peanut products early in childhood may decrease the risk of allergies, and only breastfeeding during at least the first few months of life may decrease the risk of allergic dermatitis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] There is little evidence that a mother's diet during pregnancy or breastfeeding affects the risk of allergies, although there has been some research to show that irregular cow's milk exposure might increase the risk of cow's milk allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] There is some evidence that delayed introduction of certain foods is useful, and that early exposure to potential allergens may actually be protective.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Following revisions to US and UK pediatric guidelines in 2015 and 2017 that encouraged introducing peanut products to high-risk infants at four to six months of age, one 2025 analysis found a 43% drop in the frequency of peanut allergies, with an estimated 40,000 cases prevented.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] According to that report, some pediatric experts have cautioned that real-world implementation of the guidelines may be inconsistent.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Fish oil supplementation during pregnancy is associated with a lower risk of food sensitivities.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Probiotic supplements during pregnancy or infancy may help to prevent atopic dermatitis.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Management of allergies typically involves avoiding the allergy trigger and taking medications to relieve symptoms.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy may be useful for some types of allergies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Several medications may be used to block the actions of allergic mediators, prevent cell activation, and degranulation processes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] These include antihistamines, glucocorticoids, epinephrine (adrenaline), mast cell stabilizers, and antileukotriene agents are common treatments of allergic diseases.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Anticholinergics, decongestants, and other compounds thought to impair eosinophil chemotaxis are also commonly used.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Although rare, the severity of anaphylaxis often requires epinephrine injection, and where medical care is unavailable, a device known as an epinephrine autoinjector may be used.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy is useful for environmental allergies, allergies to insect bites, and asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Its benefit for food allergies is unclear and thus not recommended.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Immunotherapy involves exposing people to larger and larger amounts of allergen in an effort to change the immune system's response.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Meta-analyses have found that injections of allergens under the skin is effective in the treatment in allergic rhinitis in children and in asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The benefits may last for years after treatment is stopped.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It is generally safe and effective for allergic rhinitis and conjunctivitis, allergic forms of asthma, and stinging insects.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] To a lesser extent, the evidence also supports the use of sublingual immunotherapy for rhinitis and asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] For seasonal allergies the benefit is small.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In this form the allergen is given under the tongue and people often prefer it to injections.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Immunotherapy is not recommended as a stand-alone treatment for asthma.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] An experimental treatment, enzyme potentiated desensitization (EPD), has been tried for decades but is not generally accepted as effective.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] EPD uses dilutions of allergen and an enzyme, beta-glucuronidase, to which T-regulatory lymphocytes are supposed to respond by favoring desensitization, or down-regulation, rather than sensitization.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] EPD has also been tried for the treatment of autoimmune diseases, but evidence does not show effectiveness.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A review found no effectiveness of homeopathic treatments and no difference compared with placebo.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The authors concluded that, based on rigorous clinical trials of all types of homeopathy for childhood and adolescent ailments, there is no convincing evidence that supports the use of homeopathic treatments.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The allergic diseases—hay fever and asthma—have increased in the Western world over the past 2–3 decades.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Increases in allergic asthma and other atopic disorders in industrialized nations, it is estimated, began in the 1960s and 1970s, with further increases occurring during the 1980s and 1990s, although some suggest that a steady rise in sensitization has been occurring since the 1920s.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The number of new cases per year of atopy in developing countries has, in general, remained much lower.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Although genetic factors govern susceptibility to atopic disease, increases in atopy have occurred within too short a period to be explained by a genetic change in the population, thus pointing to environmental or lifestyle changes.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Several hypotheses have been identified to explain this increased rate.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Increased exposure to perennial allergens may be due to housing changes and increased time spent indoors, and changes in cleanliness may decrease activation of a common immune control mechanisms or hygiene, and exacerbated by dietary changes, obesity, and decline in physical exercise.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The hygiene hypothesis maintains that high living standards and hygienic conditions expose children to fewer infections.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It is thought that reduced bacterial and viral infections early in life direct the maturing immune system away from TH1 type responses, leading to unrestrained TH2 responses that allow for an increase in allergy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Changes in rates and types of infection alone, however, have been unable to explain the observed increase in allergic disease, and recent evidence has focused attention on the importance of the gastrointestinal microbial environment.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] It is speculated that these infections exert their effect by critically altering TH1/TH2 regulation.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Important elements of newer hygiene hypotheses also include exposure to endotoxins, exposure to pets and growing up on a farm.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Some symptoms attributable to allergic diseases are mentioned in ancient sources.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Particularly, three members of the Roman Julio-Claudian dynasty (Augustus, Claudius and Britannicus) are suspected to have a family history of atopy.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The concept of "allergy" was originally introduced in 1906 by the Viennese pediatrician Clemens von Pirquet, after he noticed that patients who had received injections of horse serum or smallpox vaccine usually had quicker, more severe reactions to second injections.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Pirquet called this phenomenon "allergy" from the Ancient Greek words ἄλλος *allos* meaning "other" and ἔργον *ergon* meaning "work".
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] All forms of hypersensitivity were previously classified as allergies, and all were thought to be caused by an improper activation of the immune system.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Later, it became clear that several disease mechanisms were implicated, with a common link to disordered immune system activation.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In 1963, a new classification scheme was designed by Philip Gell and Robin Coombs that described four types of hypersensitivity reactions, known as Type I to Type IV hypersensitivity.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] With this new classification, the word *allergy*, sometimes clarified as a *true allergy*, was restricted to type I hypersensitivities (also called immediate hypersensitivity), which are characterized as rapidly developing reactions involving IgE antibodies.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] A breakthrough in understanding the mechanisms of allergy was the discovery of the antibody class labeled immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] IgE was simultaneously discovered in 1966–67 by two independent groups: Ishizaka's team at the Children's Asthma Research Institute and Hospital in Denver, USA, and by Gunnar Johansson and Hans Bennich in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Their joint paper was published in April 1969.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] Radiometric assays include the radioallergosorbent test (RAST test) method, which uses IgE-binding (anti-IgE) antibodies labeled with radioactive isotopes for quantifying the levels of IgE antibody in the blood.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The RAST methodology was invented and marketed in 1974 by Pharmacia Diagnostics AB, Uppsala, Sweden, and the acronym RAST is actually a brand name.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] In 1989, Pharmacia Diagnostics AB replaced it with a superior test named the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, which uses the newer fluorescence-labeled technology.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p01] The updated version, the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, is the only specific IgE assay the Food and Drug Administration has approved to quantitatively report to its detection limit of 0.1 kU/L.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] The medical speciality that studies, diagnoses, and treats diseases caused by allergies is called allergology.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] An allergist is a physician specially trained to manage and treat allergies, asthma, and other allergic diseases.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] Becoming an allergist/immunologist requires completion of at least nine years of training.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] After completing medical school and graduating with a medical degree, a physician will undergo three years of training in internal medicine (to become an internist) or pediatrics (to become a pediatrician).
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] Internists or pediatricians wishing to focus on the sub-specialty of allergy-immunology then complete at least an additional two years of study, called a fellowship, in an allergy/immunology training program.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] Allergists/immunologists listed as ABAI-certified have successfully passed the certifying ABAI examination following their fellowship.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] In the United Kingdom, allergy is a subspecialty of general medicine or pediatrics.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] After obtaining postgraduate exams (MRCP or MRCPCH), a doctor works for several years as a specialist registrar before qualifying for the General Medical Council specialist register.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] Allergy services may also be delivered by immunologists.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] A 2003 Royal College of Physicians report presented a case for improvement of what were felt to be inadequate allergy services in the UK.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] In 2006, the House of Lords convened a subcommittee.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] It concluded likewise in 2007 that allergy services were insufficient to deal with what the Lords referred to as an "allergy epidemic" and its social cost; it made several recommendations.
[src:t-cell/allergy-p02] Low-allergen foods are being developed, as are improvements in skin prick test predictions; evaluation of the atopy patch test, wasp sting outcomes predictions, a rapidly disintegrating epinephrine tablet, and anti-IL-5 for eosinophilic diseases.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] T cells are born from hematopoietic stem cells, found in the bone marrow.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Developing T cells then migrate to the thymus gland to develop (or mature).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] T cells derive their name from the thymus.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] After migration to the thymus, getting stimulated by thymosin, the precursor cells mature into several distinct types of T cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] T cell differentiation also continues after they have left the thymus.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Groups of specific, differentiated T cell subtypes have a variety of important functions in controlling and shaping the immune response.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] One of these functions is immune-mediated cell death, and it is carried out by two major subtypes: CD8+ "killer" (cytotoxic, Effector tumor antigen-specific T cells) and CD4+ "helper" T cells, each respectively named for the presence of proteins CD8 or CD4 on the cell surface.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] CD8+ T cells, also known as "killer T cells," are cytotoxic, referring to their ability to directly kill virus-infected cells and cancer cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] CD8+ T cells are also able to use small signalling proteins, known as cytokines, to recruit other types of cells when mounting an immune response.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] On the other hand, CD4+ T cells function as "helper cells." Unlike CD8+ killer T cells, the CD4+ helper T (TH) cells function by further activating memory B cells and cytotoxic T cells, which leads to a larger immune response.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The specific adaptive immune response regulated by the TH cell depends on its subtype (i.e., T-helper1, T-helper2, T-helper17, and regulatory T-cell), which is distinguished by the types of cytokines they secrete.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] For this reason, these regulatory T cells have also been called "suppressor" T cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These same regulatory T cells can also be co-opted by cancer cells to prevent the recognition of, and an immune response against, tumor cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] All T cells originate from c-kit+Sca1+ haematopoietic stem cells (HSC) that reside in the bone marrow.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] In some cases, the origin might be the foetal liver during embryonic development.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The HSC then differentiate into multipotent progenitors (MPP) which retain the potential to become both myeloid and lymphoid cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The process of differentiation then proceeds to a common lymphoid progenitor (CLP), which can only differentiate into T, B, or NK cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These CLP cells then migrate via the blood to the thymus, where they engraft.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Henceforth they are known as thymocytes, the immature stage of a T cell.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The earliest cells which arrived in the thymus are commonly termed *double-negative*, as they express neither the CD4 nor CD8 co-receptor.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The newly arrived CLP cells are CD4−CD8−CD44+CD25−ckit+ cells, and are termed early thymic progenitor (ETP) cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These cells will then undergo a round of division and downregulate c-kit and are termed *double-negative one* (DN1) cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] To become T cells, the thymocytes must undergo multiple DN stages as well as positive selection and negative selection.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Double negative thymocytes can be identified by the surface expression of CD2, CD5, and CD7.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Still during the double negative stages, CD34 expression stops and CD1 is expressed.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Expression of both CD4 and CD8 makes them *double positive*, and matures into either CD4+ or CD8+ cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] A critical step in T cell maturation is making a functional T cell receptor (TCR).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Each mature T cell will ultimately contain a unique TCR that reacts to a random pattern, allowing the immune system to recognize many different types of pathogens.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] This process is essential in developing immunity to threats that the immune system has not encountered before, since due to random variation there will always be at least one TCR to match any new pathogen.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] A thymocyte can only become an active T cell when it survives the process of developing a functional TCR.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The TCR consists of two major components, the alpha and beta chains.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These both contain random elements designed to produce a wide variety of different TCRs, but due to this huge variety they must be tested to make sure they work at all.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] First, the thymocytes attempt to create a functional beta chain, testing it against a 'mock' alpha chain.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Then they attempt to create a functional alpha chain.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Once a working TCR has been produced, the cells then must test if their TCR will identify threats correctly, and to do this it is required to recognize the body's major histocompatibility complex (MHC) in a process known as positive selection.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The thymocyte must also ensure that it does not react adversely to "self" antigens, called negative selection.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] If both positive and negative selection are successful, the TCR becomes fully operational and the thymocyte becomes a T cell.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] At the DN2 stage (CD44+CD25+), cells upregulate the recombination genes RAG1 and RAG2 and re-arrange the TCRβ locus, combining V-D-J recombination and constant region genes in an attempt to create a functional TCRβ chain.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] As the developing thymocyte progresses through to the DN3 stage (CD44−CD25+), the thymocyte expresses an invariant α-chain called pre-Tα alongside the TCRβ gene.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] If the rearranged β-chain successfully pairs with the invariant α-chain, signals are produced which cease rearrangement of the β-chain (and silence the alternate allele).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Although these signals require the pre-TCR at the cell surface, they are independent of ligand binding to the pre-TCR.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] If the chains successfully pair a pre-TCR forms, and the cell downregulates CD25 and is termed a DN4 cell (CD25−CD44−).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These cells then undergo a round of proliferation, and begin to re-arrange the TCRα locus during the *double-positive* stage.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The process of positive selection takes 3 to 4 days and occurs in the thymic cortex.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Double-positive thymocytes (CD4+/CD8+) migrate deep into the thymic cortex, where they are presented with self-antigens.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These self-antigens are expressed by thymic cortical epithelial cells on MHC molecules, which reside on the surface of cortical epithelial cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Only thymocytes that interact well with MHC-I or MHC-II will receive a vital "survival signal", while those that cannot interact strongly enough will receive no signal and die from neglect.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] This process ensures that the surviving thymocytes will have an 'MHC affinity' that means they will exhibit stronger binding affinity for specific MHC alleles in that organism.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The vast majority of developing thymocytes will not pass positive selection, and die during this process.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] A thymocyte's fate is determined during positive selection.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Double-positive cells (CD4+/CD8+) that interact well with MHC *class II* molecules will eventually become CD4+ "helper" cells, whereas thymocytes that interact well with MHC *class I* molecules mature into CD8+ "killer" cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] A thymocyte becomes a CD4+ cell by down-regulating expression of its CD8 cell surface receptors.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] If the cell does not lose its signal, it will continue downregulating CD8 and become a CD4+, both CD8+ and CD4+ cells are now *single positive* cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] This process does not filter for thymocytes that may cause autoimmunity.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The potentially autoimmune cells are removed by the following process of negative selection, which occurs in the thymic medulla.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Negative selection removes thymocytes that are capable of strongly binding with "self" MHC molecules.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Thymocytes that survive positive selection migrate towards the boundary of the cortex and medulla in the thymus.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] While in the medulla, they are again presented with a self-antigen presented on the MHC complex of medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs). mTECs must be Autoimmune regulator positive (AIRE+) to properly express tissue-specific antigens on their MHC *class I* peptides.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Thymocytes that interact too strongly with the self-antigen receive an apoptotic signal that leads to cell death.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] However, some of these cells are selected to become Treg cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The remaining cells exit the thymus as mature naive T cells, also known as recent thymic emigrants.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] This process is an important component of central tolerance and serves to prevent the formation of self-reactive T cells that are capable of inducing autoimmune diseases in the host.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] β-selection is the first checkpoint, where thymocytes that are able to form a functional pre-TCR (with an invariant alpha chain and a functional beta chain) are allowed to continue development in the thymus.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Next, positive selection checks that thymocytes have successfully rearranged their TCRα locus and are capable of recognizing MHC molecules with appropriate affinity.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Negative selection in the medulla then eliminates thymocytes that bind too strongly to self-antigens expressed on MHC molecules.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These selection processes allow for tolerance of self by the immune system.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Typical naive T cells that leave the thymus (via the corticomedullary junction) are self-restricted, self-tolerant, and single positive.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] About 98% of thymocytes die during the development processes in the thymus by failing either positive selection or negative selection, whereas the other 2% survive and leave the thymus to become mature immunocompetent T cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The thymus contributes fewer cells as a person ages.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] As the thymus shrinks by about 3% a year throughout middle age, a corresponding fall in the thymic production of naive T cells occurs, leaving peripheral T cell expansion and regeneration to play a greater role in protecting older people.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] T cells are grouped into a series of subsets based on their function.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] CD4 and CD8 T cells are selected in the thymus, but undergo further differentiation in the periphery to specialized cells which have different functions.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] T cell subsets were initially defined by function, but also have associated gene or protein expression patterns.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] T helper cells (TH cells) assist other lymphocytes, including the maturation of B cells into plasma cells and memory B cells, and activation of cytotoxic T cells and macrophages.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These cells are also known as **CD4+ T cells** as they express the CD4 glycoprotein on their surfaces.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Helper T cells become activated when they are presented with peptide antigens by MHC class II molecules, which are expressed on the surface of antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Once activated, they divide rapidly and secrete cytokines that regulate or assist the immune response.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These cells can differentiate into one of several subtypes, which have different roles.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Cytokines direct T cells into particular subtypes.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells (TC cells, CTLs, T-killer cells, killer T cells) destroy virus-infected cells and tumor cells, and are also implicated in transplant rejection.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These cells are defined by the expression of the CD8 protein on their cell surface.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells recognize their targets by binding to short peptides (8-11 amino acids in length) associated with MHC class I molecules, present on the surface of all nucleated cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells also produce the key cytokines IL-2 and IFNγ.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These cytokines influence the effector functions of other cells, in particular macrophages and NK cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Antigen-naive T cells expand and differentiate into memory and effector T cells after they encounter their cognate antigen within the context of an MHC molecule on the surface of a professional antigen presenting cell (e.g. a dendritic cell).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Appropriate co-stimulation must be present at the time of antigen encounter for this process to occur.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Historically, memory T cells were thought to belong to either the effector or central memory subtypes, each with their own distinguishing set of cell surface markers (see below).
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Subsequently, numerous new populations of memory T cells were discovered including tissue-resident memory T (Trm) cells, stem memory TSCM cells, and virtual memory T cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] The single unifying theme for all memory T cell subtypes is that they are long-lived and can quickly expand to large numbers of effector T cells upon re-exposure to their cognate antigen.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] By this mechanism they provide the immune system with "memory" against previously encountered pathogens.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Memory T cells may be either CD4+ or CD8+ and usually express CD45RO.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Regulatory T cells are crucial for the maintenance of immune tolerance.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Their major role is to shut down T cell–mediated immunity toward the end of an immune reaction and to suppress autoreactive T cells that escaped the process of negative selection in the thymus.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Two major classes of CD4+ Treg cells have been described—FOXP3+ Treg cells and FOXP3− Treg cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Regulatory T cells can develop either during normal development in the thymus, and are then known as thymic Treg cells, or can be induced peripherally and are called peripherally derived Treg cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] These two subsets were previously called "naturally occurring" and "adaptive" (or "induced"), respectively.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Both subsets require the expression of the transcription factor FOXP3 which can be used to identify the cells.
[src:t-cell/t-cell] Mutations of the *FOXP3* gene can prevent regulatory T cell development, causing the fatal autoimmune disease IPEX.
